# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abkhazia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abkhazia/1919-abkhazian-people-s-council-election] Elections to the People's Council were held in Abkhazia on 13 February 1919, alongside parliamentary elections in Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/1919-abkhazian-people-s-council-election] The Social Democrats won 27 of the 40 seats; 11 members of the party were Abkhazians and 11 Georgians, with the remaining five having other ethnicities.
[src:abkhazia/1919-abkhazian-people-s-council-election] Seats were also held by social federalists, an Abkhaz independent socialist group, Socialist Revolutionaries, people's democrats and colonists.
[src:abkhazia/1919-abkhazian-people-s-council-election] Of the 40 members, 18 were Abkhazian, 16 Georgian and six from other ethnic groups.
[src:abkhazia/1919-abkhazian-people-s-council-election] Following its election, the Council split along ethnic lines, with Abkhaz members of the Social Democratic Party joining the independent socialists to form an Abkhaz opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1919-abkhazian-people-s-council-election] Despite the split, the Council voted in favour of Abkhazia being an autonomous region of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The riots started as an Abkhaz protest against opening of a branch of Tbilisi State University in Sukhumi, and concluded with looting of the Georgian school which was expected to house the new university on 16 July 1989.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The ensuing violence quickly degenerated into a large-scale inter-ethnic confrontation.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] By the time when the Soviet army managed to temporarily bring the situation under control, the riots resulted in at least 18 dead and 448 injured, mostly Georgians.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The first case of inter-ethnic violence in Georgia, it effectively marked the start of the Georgian-Abkhaz conflict.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Abkhazia, being part of medieval Kingdom of Georgia and western Georgian Kingdom of Imereti, joined the Georgia in modern times as recently as 1918 as an autonomous entity.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] After Soviet annexation of Georgia, from 1921 until 1931, Abkhazia was a quasi-independent Soviet republic, the Socialist Soviet Republic of Abkhazia (SSR Abkhazia), united with the Georgian SSR in a special treaty status but not fully subservient.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] This arrangement ended when the SSR Abkhazia was downgraded into the Abkhaz ASSR and fully under the control of the Georgian SSR.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] In 1956, Georgians protested a policy of de-stalinization of Nikita Khrushchev, inflamed by sarcastic and bitter manner in which Khrushchev emphasized Stalin's Georgian character.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Thus, Stalin's denigration was seen as a symbol for the mistreatment of Georgian national consciousness at the hands of the Soviet rulers.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The protests were violently dispersed by the Soviet authorities, with estimates of the number of casualties ranging from several dozens to several hundred.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The separatist elements in Abkhazia capitalized on these circumstances to win over the support of the Soviet government and launched counter-protests in 1957, including against autonomous status of Abkhazia within Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Anti-Georgian telegrams, letters and statements were sent to the central Soviet authorities in Moscow by the Abkhaz, while the Georgian inscriptions in Abkhazia were destroyed or falsified.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The Soviet government responded by granting significant privileges to the Abkhaz.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] These protests were repeated again in 1967, and in 1978, the latter capitalizing on embarrassment faced by the Soviet government when it had to concede to the Georgian protesters who thus successfully defended the constitutional status of Georgian language in the Georgian SSR.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Therefore, each time the Abkhaz protests resulted in the Soviet government favoring the Abkhaz and granting ethnic-based privileges in the Abkhaz SSR.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] These privileges included the upgrading of the Sukhum Pedagogical Institute into a full university, Abkhaz State University, but also wide over-representation of the Abkhaz in the nomenklatura.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] As the Georgian dissidents began to campaign for the Georgian independence and mobilized large number of protesters in the late 1980s, on 17 June 1988, an 87-page document, known as the 'Abkhazian Letter', was sent to Mikhail Gorbachev and the rest of the Soviet leadership.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Signed by 60 leading Abkhaz Communists, it outlined "the grievances the Abkhaz felt", and argued that despite the concessions of 1978, autonomy had largely been ignored in the region.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Thus, it asked for Abkhazia to be removed from the Georgian SSR, and to be "restored as a full Soviet republic, akin to the SSR Abkhazia".
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Further issues occurred on 18 March 1989.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Around 37,000 people met at the village of Lykhny, a traditional meeting spot for the Abkhaz, and signed what became known as the Lykhny Declaration.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] It once again called for Abkhazia to become a separate republic like it was between 1921 and 1931.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The Declaration, which unlike the prior 'Abkhazian Letter' was made public immediately saw mass opposition demonstrations from the Georgian community in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] By April, the demonstrations had become increasingly violent.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Abkhaz rioters attacked buses carrying Georgian students in Gagra, Bzipi, and Gudauta.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] At a plenum of the Georgian central committee the following day the Communist party first secretary, Jumber Patiashvili, resigned and was replaced by the former head of the Georgian KGB, Givi Gumbaridze.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The 9 April tragedy removed the last vestiges of credibility from the Soviet regime in Georgia and pushed many Georgians into radical opposition to the Soviet Union, and exacerbated ethnic tensions between Georgians and other groups, in particular the Abkhaz and Ossetians.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The issue of a university had always been very sensitive in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Sukhumi State University was established in 1978 as a part of the concessions towards the Abkhaz secessionist demands, which in its turn was triggered by the Georgian national mobilization in defense of their language and culture.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The university had three sectors: Abkhaz, Georgian, and Russian.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] However, Georgian students repeatedly complained of discrimination at the hands of their Abkhaz and Russian lectors and administration.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] In the aftermath of the 9 April events, Georgian students at Sukhumi State University started a hunger strike, calling for the Georgian sector of the university to be transformed into a branch of Tbilisi State University, and in effect controlled by Georgians and not Abkhaz.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Joined by students and faculty from the Subtropical Institute, this was part of a campaign started by ethnic Georgians in Abkhazia for greater cultural separation, and more clear division between the two ethnic groups.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Aware it would cause unrest in Abkhazia, the authorities approved the measure on 14 May.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The Supreme Soviet in Moscow also launched a commission, which ruled that the Georgians had no authority to establish the university, as that was solely under its purview.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] They concluded that a region the size of Abkhazia had no need for two universities.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Despite the ruling against the legality of the university, entrance exams were scheduled for 15 July.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Attempts by Abkhaz to photograph the crowds of Georgians congregated in the city is said to have started the violence.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] By 7:00pm the university was under attack.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Late on 16 July, a crowd of five thousand Abkhaz, many of whom were armed, surged into the building.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Several members of the Georgian exam commission were beaten up, and the school was looted.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] This set off a chain of events that produced further casualties and destruction as the both sides engaged in armed fighting for several days to come.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] That evening, Abkhaz and Georgians began mobilizing all over Abkhazia and western Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Svans, an ethnic Georgian subgroup from northeastern Abkhazia, and Abkhaz from the town of Tkvarcheli in Abkhazia clashed in a shootout that lasted all night and intermittently for several days afterward.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Meanwhile, up to 25,000 Georgians from western Georgia, and the predominantly Georgian Gali district in southern Abkhazia, gathered near Ochamchire.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Soviet Interior Ministry troops were sent in to restore order, and by 17 July the violence had largely dissipated.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The July events in Abkhazia left at least 18 dead and 448 injured, of whom, according to official accounts, 302 were Georgians.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] It also marked the first case of inter-ethnic violence in Georgia; while previous protests and demonstrations had occurred in Abkhazia, none had seen any casualties.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Although a continuous presence of the Interior Ministry troops maintained a precarious peace in the region, outbursts of violence did occur, and the Soviet government made no progress toward solving any of the inter-ethnic problems.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] At the same time, they accused the Soviet government of manipulating ethnic issues to curb Georgia's otherwise irrepressible independence movement.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Tensions remained high in Abkhazia, and saw the Abkhaz totally disregard Georgian authority in the region.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] This was confirmed on 25 August 1990, when the Abkhaz Supreme Soviet passed a declaration, "On Abkhazia's State Sovereignty," which gave supremacy to Abkhaz laws over Georgian ones.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The same day the Supreme Soviet also declared Abkhazia to be a full union republic within the Soviet Union.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] This was countered by accusations from Georgians that the Abkhaz were not the original inhabitants of the region, a claim first promoted by Georgian scholars in the 1950s but without any serious academic or historic basis.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The victory of a nationalist coalition in October 1990 only further led to increased issues, as the newly elected Chairman of the Georgian Supreme Soviet, Zviad Gamsakhurdia, was outspoken in his desire to reduce the autonomy of the non-Georgian population in the country.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] A power-sharing deal was agreed upon in August 1991, dividing electoral districts by ethnicity, with the 1991 elections held under this format, though it did not last.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] However, with the breakdown of the Gamsakhurida government in Georgia, and efforts by Eduard Shevardnadze to delegitimize Gamsakhurdia by failing to honour agreements he signed, and Abkhaz desires to utilize the ongoing Georgian Civil War, it fell apart.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Thus on 23 July 1992, the Abkhaz Supreme Soviet re-instated the 1925 constitution, which had called Abkhazia a sovereign state, albeit one in treaty union with Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] Georgia responded militarily on 14 August, starting an offensive.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] The ensuing war would last until September 1993, and lead to the ongoing Abkhaz–Georgian conflict.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] In the aftermath of the 1992–1993 war, the Sukhumi branch of Tbilisi State University, which had remained open, was relocated to Tbilisi as the city fell out of Georgian control.
[src:abkhazia/1989-sukhumi-riots] It was re-established in Tbilisi in December 1993, and remains there.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The **1991–1992 Georgian coup d'état**, also known as the **Tbilisi War**, or the **Putsch of 1991–1992**, was an internal military conflict that took place in the newly independent Republic of Georgia following the fall of the Soviet Union, from 22 December 1991 to 6 January 1992.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The coup, which triggered the Georgian Civil War, pitted factions of the National Guard loyal to President Zviad Gamsakhurdia against several paramilitary organizations unified at the end of 1991 under the leadership of warlords Tengiz Kitovani, Jaba Ioseliani and Tengiz Sigua.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The Tbilisi War ended with the exile of the first democratically elected president of Georgia, after two weeks of violent clashes on Rustaveli Avenue, the main thoroughfare of Tbilisi, mainly consisting of a siege of the Georgian Parliament building, where Gamsakhurdia was isolated in a bunker.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Following Gamsakhurdia's fall, a Military Council, led by Kitovani, Ioseliani and Sigua, took power in Tbilisi and assured the return of Eduard Shevardnadze, the former Soviet Georgian leader and the last Soviet Foreign Affairs Minister, to hand over power to him.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] During the civil war, the supporters of the ousted president staged an unsuccessful revolt to return him to power.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Shevardnadze gradually sidelined Kitovani and Ioseliani, and ruled the country until he was ousted in the bloodless 2003 "Rose Revolution".
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] In 2005, the Parliament of Georgia passed a resolution denouncing the events of 1991–1992 as an "anticonstitutional armed coup d'état".
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] According to a 2020 poll by the Caucasus Research Resource Centers, 76% of Georgians think that the coup was harmful for Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Following the Red Army invasion of 1921 and Bolshevik takeover, Georgia became part of the Soviet Union (formed in 1922).
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Despite having formally a status of a sovereign "union republic" (the Socialist Soviet Republic of Georgia), nationalist feelings demanding independence developed in Georgia largely in the 1970s, feelings that were repeated across the Soviet Union.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The Tbilisi Tragedy, coupled with the military failure in Afghanistan and the collapse of the Iron Curtain that separated Western world from the Eastern Bloc led to a chain reaction that saw the Baltic states declare their independence in 1990.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Soon, Soviet authorities, under pressure of mass revolts, allowed multi-party elections in October 1990, which saw Round Table, the alliance led by Zviad Gamsakhurdia, winning a majority of the seats in the Supreme Council, which ended 69 years of Communist Party.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] However, the previously united Georgian nationalist opposition split into two main factions in May 1990.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Gamsakhurdia's tenure began with groups such as the National Democratic Party of Gia Chanturia and the National Independence Party of Irakli Tsereteli challenging his authority with street demonstrations, rallies, hunger strikes etc.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The dissolution of the Soviet Union led to a rebirth of tensions between certain ethnic groups across the Union republics, Georgia being no exception.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] *Adamon Nikhas*, a communist movement in South Ossetia, started to demand greater autonomy from Tbilisi as early as the late 1980s, a request denied by the central government in November 1989.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Tensions between Tbilisi and Tskhinvali rose until a declaration of sovereignty of South Ossetia from Georgia within the Soviet Union in September 1990, following which Tbilisi retaliated by abolishing the Autonomous Oblast of South Ossetia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] In January 1991, the militarization of the conflict divided Tskhinvali in two, thus launching a civil war that lasted until June 1992 and that lead to the creation of the separatist Republic of South Ossetia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Meanwhile, Abkhazia fell into ethnic conflict.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] As early as 1989, violent clashes between Georgian and Abkhaz nationalists plunged the region into violent conflict that later extended into a "war of laws" between the legislatures of Tbilisi and of the Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic of Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 9 April 1991, two years after the Tbilisi Tragedy and ten days after a largely victorious referendum on the subject, the Georgian Supreme Council declared the country's independence, appointing famed dissident and Georgian nationalist Zviad Gamsakhurdia as interim president.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The latter was eventually elected president with 86% of the vote in an election that saw an 83% participation rate on 26 May.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] In January 1991, Zviad Gamsakhurdia signed an executive decree creating the National Guard of Georgia, a prelude to the future Georgian Army, under the jurisdiction of the new Ministry of Internal Affairs.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] At its head, he appointed Tengiz Kitovani, recently elected to the Supreme Council of Georgia with Gamsakhurdia's party, with a mission to recruit 20,000 capable soldiers.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Meanwhile, the government attempted to reign in the various paramilitary organizations which had recently emerged in the country and were utilized by the political forces.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The first signs of crisis also developed within the government on 9 August 1991, with an argument in the Supreme Council of Georgia between Gamsakhurdia and Vazha Adamia, the leader of the Merab Kostava Society, a political and paramilitary organization that was part of the Round Table coalition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Adamia, who was head of the parliamentary commission on defense, national security and order, would eventually resign in September 1991, with his organization joining the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] According to some sources, the confrontation was caused by the conflict between Adamia and the head of the National Guard of Georgia, Tengiz Kitovani.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Kitovani largely collaborated with Gamsakhurdia's war in South Ossetia, launching several assaults on the regions outside of Tbilisi's control between February and June 1991.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] However, the situation changed drastically during the summer of that same year.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 18 August, three ministers, including Prime Minister Tengiz Sigua, announced their support for the opposition and resigned from their posts, accusing the President of becoming a "totalitarian demagogue." Gamsakhurdia took himself the helm of the Ministries of Foreign Affairs and Justice.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] An attempted putsch in Moscow the next day brought a new controversy.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The State Committee on the State of Emergency ordered all republics, including Georgia, to disband their new armed forces.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Gamsakhurdia issued a presidential decree bringing the troops entirely within the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The position of commander of the National Guard was abolished, with Kitovani being dismissed.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] According to Gamsakhurdia, he never had the intention to disband the National Guard, and he simply reorganized it to protect it from the Moscow coup leaders.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Gamsakhurdia later would allege in October 1991 that Kitovani together with Sigua had been threatening him with armed mutiny in spring of 1991 over disagreements on cadre policy.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] In response to his decree, Kitovani and the opposition accused Gamsakhurdia of secretly siding with the Moscow coup plotters.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Tengiz Kitovani, opposing his decision, left Tbilisi with a force of around 15,000 armed men and set up camp in the Rkoni Gorge, around 40 kilometers north of the capital.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] He was soon joined by Tengiz Sigua and former Foreign Affairs Minister Giorgi Khoshtaria.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Meanwhile, on 26 August Gamsakhurdia banned the Communist Party for allegedly supporting the Moscow coup, which had 60 seats in the Supreme Council at the time.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Tbilisi converted the local bureau of the KGB into a Department of National Security, which became a Ministry a few weeks later.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] A National Security Council was also created, proving that Gamsakhurdia wished to see a military infrastructure independent from Moscow.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 2 September, the situation becomes violent when demonstrations organized by the People's Front of Georgia and the NDP to ask for Jaba Ioseliani's freedom were dispersed by MIA forces.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] According to the non-government organization Human Rights Watch, the protesters, assembled on Rustaveli Avenue, were beaten with batons, while soldiers shot at the crowd.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The incident resulted in three civilians getting injured.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Following the clash, the situation in the central Tbilisi progressively spiralled out of control.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 11 September, the 27 political parties signed a resignation request for Gamsakhurdia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Meanwhile, on 9 September, Gamsakhurdia issued a decree creating the Defence Ministry which incorporated the National Guard under his personal control.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 17 September, Giorgi Chanturia, leader of the NDP, was arrested by law enforcement, being accused of being behind the construction of barricades.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Giorgi Khaindrava, a member of the Georgian National Congress political party, was also arrested.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Gamsakhurdia called his followers from the all provinces of Georgia to gather in Tbilisi and clear the streets from barricades.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 21 September, the government supporters launched an assault to clear the Rustaveli Avenue from the barricades blocking the street.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 22 September, a group of several dozens of protesters who were on hungerstrike in front of Parliament were violently dispersed by 250 presidential guards and around 200 "furies", women partisans of Gamsakhurdia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On the night of 22–23 September, the situation fell even further into violence when around 5,000 Gamsakhurdia supporters, led by deputy Avtandil Rtskhiladze, entered the headquarters of the NDP, where they faced some 800 members of the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 23 September, the rebel factions of the Georgian National Guard led by Tengiz Kitovani entered Tbilisi to support the opposition in the clashes and seized the television station.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 24 September, Zviad Gamsakhurdia proclaimed a state of emergency.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] One of the first armed clashes which resulted in casualties occurred on 25 September, when the rebel units of the National Guard attempted to take over a power station in Tbilisi but were driven back by police.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Since the end of September 1991, Tbilisi was a divided city.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The Gldani, Nadzaladevi, and Didube neighborhoods, as well as the south and center parts of Rustaveli Avenue (housing government buildings) remained under the military control of Zviad Gamsakhurdia, who had started to isolate himself within the Supreme Council building.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Neighborhoods located between the Marx-Engels-Lenin Institute (29 Rustaveli Ave.) and the Tbilisi State University (1 Chavchavadze Ave.) were loyal to the opposition, while the Mkhedrioni militia used the rest of Chavchavadze Avenue as its training ground.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] In the meantime, the neighborhoods of Vake and Saburtalo, populated by members of the Soviet intelligentsia, remained neutral.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Each side was commanding 1,000 to 3,000 soldiers.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Soviet Transcaucasian Military District, still based near Tbilisi, used the internal chaos to sell weapons to both sides in order to worsen the situation.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 3 October, with the mediation of the Georgian Orthodox Church, the sides reached an agreement on the withdrawal of the Kitovani's militia outside of Tbilisi.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] However, Kitovani's National Guard withdrew to the Tbilisi Sea, on the outskirts of Tbilisi, which left it unclear whether this action was in accordance with the agreement.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] At the same time, on 4 October, the opposition started a massive rally at the direction of the Supreme Council building, which was met by the Gamsakhurdia supporters and resulted in armed clashes.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Meanwhile, the units of the National Guard still supporting President, headed by Loti Kobalia, surrounded Kitovani's units near Tbilisi sea picketing them, although a major clash was averted with only small skirmishes.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Ultimately, the government forces secured light victories and on 8 October, during the Supreme Council session chaired by Gamsakhurdia, the incident on 4–5 October was officially classified as the coup attempt.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Kitovani and his former National Guard would remain in the surroundings of Tbilisi until December.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The period after the 4–5 October is assessed by the historian Dimitri Shvelidze as a prelude for the main battle, where both sides were gathering forces, searching for allies, weapons, money, and other resources.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] A temporary return to peace allowed Gamsakhurdia to suspend the law on political parties, effectively banning all parties during the state of emergency on 5 November, before closing the newspaper *Sakartvelo-Sakinphorm*.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Valery Kvaratskhelia, a TV producer, was arrested on 2 October, and Goga Khindasheli, regional secretary of the NDP in Samtredia, joined others in prison soon.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On the night of 21–22 October, eleven members of the NDP were arrested as well, while Temur Zhorzholiani, leader of the Monarchist Party, was arrested on 15 November.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] They are all imprisoned in the Ortachala Prison in the south of Tbilisi.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 12 December, the US Secretary of State James Baker gave speech at the Princeton University, where he talked about the American policy in the post-Soviet world.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 19 December, Tengiz Kitovani offered an ultimatum to Zviad Gamsakhurdia, asking for his immediate resignation.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 20 December 1991, Tengiz Kitovani returned to Tbilisi, where he unified his troops with those of the Mkhedrioni and the Merab Kostava Society militia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The next day, the Soviet Union was formally abolished and Georgia refused to join the Commonwealth of Independent States.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Zviad Gamsakhurdia barricaded himself in the basement of the Parliament building.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] After having arrived in the capital, Kitovani announced, "We did not fight [Gamsakhurdia] actively while international opinion on the authoritarian nature of his personal dictatorship wasn't clear.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The lack of organization within governmental troops and the defection of a large amount of forces during the coup makes any attempt to estimate the size of troops loyal to Zviad Gamsakhurdia difficult.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] While some western sources claim between 1,000 and 2,000 combatants fight for Gamsakhurdia, the latter estimates himself having 5,000 soldiers on his side.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Sources become blurrier in the second week of the coup.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Gia Karkarashvili, who leads the Military Council's war efforts, claims that the other side has no more than 250–300 men by 4 January, while the Russian news agency *Interfax* reported 300–500 Zviadist soldiers the day before.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Other Russian sources, meanwhile, estimate nearly 1,500 Zviadists, 60% of which being armed, on 5 January.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The Military Council, which represents the opposition, declared during the conflict that the majority of pro-Gamsakhurdia soldiers were 18 or 19 years old and were coerced into fighting.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] According to the council, there was only a very small group of armed fighters belonging to the government's OMON, a special, highly trained branch of the National Guard.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Some of those who fought on Gamsakhurdia's side were reportedly devoted female followers of his dressed in black, known as "furies" or the "Black Pantyhose Battalion".
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] A youth militia from the mountainous region of Svaneti, nicknamed "Lemi" (ლემი, or "Lion" in Svan) also fought for the president.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The participation of foreign mercenaries remains a controversial subject, denied by Gamsakhurdia supporters.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] However, during a 4 January press conference by the Military Council, the latter condemns the use of Chechen mercenaries sent by Ichkeria President and close Gamsakhurdia ally Dzhokhar Dudayev.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Jaba Ioseliani, leader of the Mkhedrioni militia, states then that "Jokhar Dudaiev's position is unacceptable and misplaced, but hope remains that this quid pro quo can be fixed." On 5 January, four Ukrainian mercenaries probably working as snipers for the government are detained by the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The majority of opposition troops come from rebel factions of the National Guard that followed Tengiz Kitovani during his August 1991 mutiny.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] However, while an estimated 15,000 to 20,000 members of the Guard pledged allegiance to the opposition's struggle, only a small part of these combatants participated in the Tbilisi battle, while the other soldiers remain in South Ossetia or Abkhazia fighting in the 1991–1992 South Ossetia War.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Jaba Ioseliani commands a militia of 600 to 5,000 soldiers that operate under the *Mkhedrioni* standard.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] This militia remains under the direct leadership of Ioseliani, even after the opposition's unification after the 2 January 1992 proclamation of the Military Council, and it is this militia that would cause the 3 January massacre.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] The Merab Kostava Society, which was organized as a political movement in 1990 before becoming an armed militia led by Vazha Adamia, joined the rebel National Guard as early as 20 December 1991.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Starting on 22 December, *Tetri Artsivi* (თეთრი არწივი, or "White Eagle"), a paramilitary group of around 80 men led by warlord Gia Karkarashvili and operating in the South Ossetia war, leaves Tskhinvali to assist the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] This militia would be used to put siege on Tbilisi and block all routes leading to the capital.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Karkarashvili would later become one of the main figures in the Military Council, before taking the post of Minister of Defense during the Abkhazia War.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] On 31 December 1991, Gia Chanturia announced that the Union of Afghans, a militia made of more than 1,000 veterans from the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, joined the opposition forces.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] According to the theory by historian and close Gamsakhurdia ally Leila Tsomaia, Zviad Gamsakhurdia had been given time until 07:00 on 22 December to contact Boris Yeltsin and pledge Georgia's membership into the Commonwealth of Independent States.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Gamsakhurdia's refusal to do so would have been what jump-started the hostilities.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] This version is confirmed by the president, who accused Yeltsin of being behind the coup.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] During the conflict, accusations of Russian assistance to one side or another were regularly made by both the president and the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Despite these allegations, Yuri Grekov, First Vice-Commander of the Military District of Transcaucasia of the Soviet Army, denied any Soviet involvement in the conflict, while striking an agreement on the Soviet troops' remaining in Georgia after Gamsakhurdia's departure.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] According to that letter, lacking the interference of the Russian soldiers, "Gamsakhurdia supporters would have had a guaranteed victory." This version of the facts revealed also an involvement by Russian soldiers during the battle around the Broadcasting Tower of Tbilisi.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] However, another theory was provided by Greek strategist Spyros Demetriou, who revealed in a 2002 study the large implication of Soviet forces in the civil war.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Shortly after Gamsakhurdia's election in 1990, Moscow authorities authorized a covert operation of introducing a large artillery of undocumented weapons into Georgia through Armenia and Azerbaijan, to be distributed among the several paramilitary groups set up by Georgian nationalists.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] As soon as early 1991, large caches of AK-47s and Makarov PMs were introduced on the Vaziani Military Base and into the Georgian stations of the DOSAAF.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Nine Georgian, three Ossetian, and three Abkhaz militias were thus armed before the beginning of the civil war.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] During the coup itself, Sufian Bepayev may have provided weapons and armed vehicles to both sides.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] According to some sources, he may have begun by offering free weapons at the beginning of the coup, before starting to sell them: $200 to $300 per AK-47, $800 per Makarov PM, and $5,000 to $8,000 per armed vehicle.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] According to the Georgian Defense Foundation, the National Guard received, between 21 December 1991 and 6 January 1992, nearly 200 AK-47s, 50 RPG-7s, two SVD Dragunov rifles, and 200 Makarov PMs.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Following the Military Council's victory, a special battalion of the National Guard was formed on 10 January and was entirely equipped by Russian military bases.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p01] Some analyze this weapons distribution scheme to be the natural result of the lack of order among remaining Soviet armies after the downfall of the USSR, given the harsh economic conditions of the Caucasus and the corruption of high-ranking military officials.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] As soon as Kitovani arrives in Tbilisi, battle plans are put into place.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While the National Guard and government leaders fortify themselves within the Parliament building, Tengiz Sigua takes over the Tbilisi Hotel on Rustaveli Avenue, less than 250 meters away from Parliament, designating the building as the opposition's military headquarters.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 21 December, Otar Litanishvili, a commander of the Mkhedrioni, brings a detailed map of the capital within the HQ and military leaders plan the coming attacks.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Tengiz Kitovani takes command of the upcoming assault on Parliament, being the most knowledgeable of the building's infrastructure, from his time as head of the National Guard.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The opposition's preparations are largely made on the night of 21–22 December.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Giorgi Arveladze, a Mkhedrioni officer, is sent to inspect the surroundings of Parliament to confirm the location of governmental troops and soon, Rustaveli Avenue is blocked from the public, with both sides using buses and armed vehicles to isolate the most popular street of Tbilisi.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] His militia is armed with 50 AK-47s, 3 AKS74s, 20 AKS-74Us, and 50 cases of grenades.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] With just the Kashveti Church serving as a buffer between both camps, government authorities send Mayor Tamaz Vashadze of Tbilisi and deputy Avtandil Rtskhiladze on a negotiation mission one last time before the beginning of the hostilities, but the two are kidnapped by Sigua's forces.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Around 07:30, Murtaz Shualashvili orders the first fire against Parliament and Karkarashvili launches four rockets on the Parliament building, inaugurating two weeks of violence.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] According to a New York Times report, the opposition refuses to accept any responsibility with the first attack.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Throughout 22 December, both sides use rockets, grenades, and automatic weapons to fight each other.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Kashveti Church, which houses opposition soldiers, becomes a target of governmental forces.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Gamsakhurdia household, nicknamed "Colchis Bell", catches fire, but the family, under governmental protection during the coup, remains safe.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Parliament building is entirely isolated, notably because of the preceding cut of all communication cables leading to and from Gamsakhurdia's bunker, a cut that was ordered by the President a few months before under the advice of his National Security Adviser, Otar Khatiashvili.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Khatiashvili joins the opposition on the first day of fighting, while Communications Minister Phelix Tkebuchava, stays formally inside the government but collaborates with coup leaders by cutting the phone lines of Parliament.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Throughout the day, rebels managed to enter Parliament twice, but governmental forces push back both times, before asking for a negotiation.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The latter soon fails and the battle starts anew, while Sigua contacts Gamsakhurdia and warns him, "Your faults will not happen any longer.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] You should have resigned a long time ago.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Kutateladze then takes a helicopter and is sent by Sigua and Tengiz Kitovani to Zugdidi, in western Georgia, to prevent the formation of pro-Gamsakhurdia forces.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Tamaz Ninua, deputy Foreign Affairs Minister, also joins the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] During the afternoon, Ilia II, Catholicos-Patriarch of the Georgian Orthodox Church, makes an appearance on Rustaveli Avenue, asking both sides to agree on peace, while remaining neutral during the conflict, a position that would later be criticized heavily by some Gamsakhurdia supporters.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] During the evening, Gamsakhurdia, remaining in his bunker with his family, addressed the nation, pretending that his forces had defeated opposition troops and pledging to not resign.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Between seven and 17 people are killed during the first day of battle.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The conflict intensifies on 23 December during a new direct assault against the Parliament, organized in the morning but rebuffed by the National Guard.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The airport and TV and radio stations are temporarily closed.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Russian TV, meanwhile, provides footage of vehicles armed with rocket launchers pointed at the Parliament building, before the beginning of a second attack against the structure, led by Tengiz Sigua himself, who predicts an imminent victory.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The second attack on 23 December results in a temporary victory of the presidential forces, but the Art Museum of Georgia, across the street from the Parliament, catches fire.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Russian press agency *TASS* writes about the event that several people are stuck inside the museum with no way out, while fire brigades have no access because of the opposition blockade on the street.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Gamsakhurdia recalls the remaining parts of his National Guard in Tbilisi in order to attempt a breach through the opposition's barricades outside the city, thus putting an end to any large Georgian military presence in South Ossetia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While increasing the blockade around Tbilisi, Tengiz Sigua and Tengiz Kitovani offer a peace proposal to Gamsakhurdia on 24 December.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The plan offers to treat members of government with safe conduct in exchange of the immediate resignation of the president, an offer refused by the head of state.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] At the end of the day, some international reports estimated the number of dead between 23 and 50 Georgians and 168 to 200 injured.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Russian television shows footage of civilians evacuating the bodies of victims during the evening.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 25 December, the number of dead grows to 30–80 victims, according to US media.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The most severe battle of the coup d'état takes place on 27 December when Tengiz Kitovani's troops penetrate inside the Parliament and put fire to the first floor of the building with gasoline.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 28 December, it becomes clear that government forces have lost all control outside of the presidential bunker and Tengiz Kitovani, followed by a Mkhedrioni detachment, captures the former Soviet office of the KGB in the Gldani neighborhood, where several opposition leaders are imprisoned.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Eight prisoners are freed and brought to Rustaveli Avenue to encourage fighters, including Giorgi Chanturia, Giorgi Khaindrava, and the titular head of the Mkhedrioni, Jaba Ioseliani.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The latter takes back his control over the militia and Chanturia announces that the civil war must continue until the resignation of Gamsakhurdia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On their way, the Kitovani troops burn down several buildings of strategic importance, including the National Bank of Georgia and the Ministry of Internal Affairs, leading to the destruction of nearly 210,000 documents (or 80% of the entirety) of governmental archives from the Soviet era.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] At the end of 28 December, the number of dead had risen to at least 42, and 260 injured.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 31 December, Nodar Giorgadze, deputy minister of defense and leader of a militia made up of veterans from the Afghanistan War, publicly asks for Gamsakhurdia's resignation, leading to his arrest.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] He is soon joined by Murman Omanidze, the Foreign Affairs Minister and one of Gamsakhurdia's closest advisers, following his failed negotiating trip to Russia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 1 January 1992, opposition forces capture the Broadcasting Tower of Tbilisi, allowing them to control televised messages.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 2 January 1992, opposition leaders, assembled within the Academy of Sciences, announced the establishment of a Military Council.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Council becomes the only government recognized by members of the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While the complete makeup of the council's administration is never made public, Tengiz Kitovani and Jaba Ioseliani proclaim themselves Council leaders, while nominating Tengiz Sigua as head of government and Prime Minister and the Supreme Council is dissolved.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Aleksandre Chikvaidze, the Russian ambassador to the Netherlands, is appointed Foreign Affairs Minister, former Soviet military commissar Levan Sharashenidze is named Minister of Defense, and Vakhtang Razmadze becomes the Chief Prosecutor.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Theoretically, the Gamsakhurdia government remains the only legitimate entity recognized by major foreign powers, but it isn't clear which government is recognized by Laos, Ethiopia, and Iraq, which recognize Georgian independence the day of the council's creation.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Kitovani and Ioseliani sign together all the junta's decrees, including a first decree deposing the Gamsakhurdia cabinet, before abolishing the Constitution in a second decree.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] By ordering such moves, opposition leaders claimed to want to restore the old Democratic Republic of Georgia's 1921 Constitution, but this restoration will only happen in late February and the country operates under the junta's unilateral control for a month.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In order to convince the civilian population of the opposition's democratic intentions, the Military Council announces the formation of a consultative assembly made of political and intellectual figures ("open to all, except Zviad Gamsakhurdia").
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] A curfew is established the same day by the junta across Tbilisi, prohibiting anyone from leaving their homes from 23:00 to 06:00.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Zviad Gamsakhurdia, whose troops consist of a just a few hundred guards at this point, asks, from his bunker, the Georgian people to ignore the Military Council's decrees and to follow only "the Constitution, the laws of the Republic and those of its democratically-elected government".
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The main battle on 2 January takes place during the evening when, around 18:00, governmental troops attack with trace fire the Iveria Hotel, controlled by the opposition and less than one kilometer north of the Parliament building and which includes a Red Cross station.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The opposition retaliates from the Academy of Arts building, leading to a fierce battle on Rustaveli Avenue until 22:00.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] By the end of 2 January, Gamsakhurdia's Health Ministry counted a total of 73 dead and 400 injured since the beginning of the conflict.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Gia Karkarashvili is named military governor of Tbilisi by the Military Council.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While Tbilisi falls into chaos, the rest of Georgia (except for South Ossetia) remains more or less calm during the first week of the conflict.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] However, the events affected some rural zones in January 1992.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Thus, while Georgian television falls under opposition control on 1 January, all programming is stopped in western Georgia, which had remained loyal to Gamsakhurdia, thanks to the capture of the broadcasting tower of Kutaisi by Zviadists.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In the same manner, while a majority of the country stops receiving newspapers following the closure of printers in Tbilisi during the coup, western Georgia keeps its pro-Gamsakhurdia newspapers thanks to the printers of Kutaisi.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 4 January, Zviad Gamsakhurdia signs a decree from his bunker requiring all municipal and regional governments outside of Tbilisi to organize a large-scale mobilization of troops against the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] This order requires the mobilization to take place until 7 January and mandates the local governments to open mobilization centers to welcome all military conscripts, aged 20 to 45 years old.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Local authorities are also under the obligation to organize transport for this theoretical army.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] However, without a National Guard, this decree cannot be enforced.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In response, the Military Council announces the abolition of local governments and declares its intent to appoint local governors loyal to the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] According to an announcement by the council, the majority of local government centers fell into the junta's control by 18:30 on 4 January.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] However, the country still includes some cities loyal to the President; a gun battle takes place at the Rustavi City Hall, 25 kilometers south of the capital, between the local government and Military Council troops, on 5 January.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 3 January, it becomes clear that the Gamsakhurdia government has no longer enough forces to defeat the opposition.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] However, the Western press questions the strength of the opposition, notably because of the bunker's advantageous position, but also because of the lack of any decisive force by either side.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While the Military Council issued a new decree forbidding all protestations, an assembly of 3,000 to 4,000 Gamsakhurdia supporters organize a demonstration around 12:00 on 3 January, starting from a railway station several miles from the battlefield.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The protesters, including mainly middle-aged men and women, carry the President's portrait, while chanting his name ("Zviadi!") and walking toward Rustaveli Avenue.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] After just 15 minutes, a car transporting masked men of the Mkhedrioni throws smoke bombs on the crowd, which only angers and energizes it, while encouraging applause from civilians on their balconies.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] But a group of eight to ten masked men wearing sunglasses to hide their identities, form a line in front of the demonstrators and start shooting blanks to disperse the crowd.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] A few instants later, real bullets are fired at the protesters, who disperse violently while some take refuge behind cars.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Two protesters are immediately killed and several are injured, including two more who would die a few days later.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The events of 3 January increase the rhetoric between both sides.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Jaba Ioseliani announces during a press conference that the decision to violently disperse the demonstration came directly from the Military Council, due to the junta's decree banishing all demonstrations.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] He called the massacre "normal" and threatened to repeat the orders if Tbilisi residents continued to violate the council's decrees, while apologizing to four journalists who had their equipment confiscated by opposition forces.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Ioseliani accuses the elite OMON forces of Gamsakhurdia of having provoked the Mkhedrioni soldiers.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Zviad Gamsakhurdia compared, during an interview with British TV station Sky News, the Military Council to "terrorists and criminals" on 4 January.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] During that same interview, he refused a new offer to negotiate his resignation with the opposition and compared the shooting to the January 1991 events in Lithuania, when Soviet troops shot and killed several protesters fighting for independence.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] At 18:00, Sigua announces on television an ultimatum to the President, giving him until 08:00 the next morning to resign.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Military Council temporarily ceases fire and blocks all access to the Parliament building, except for the street behind the building in order to allow Gamsakhurdia soldiers to leave the battlefield.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Gamsakhurdia's refusal leads to tensions within the bunker, escalating when two parties cause a violent brawl due to a disagreement on the follow-up strategy.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] After shots are fired within the compound, a large part of the fighters leaves the Parliament building and, by 20:00, only 500 guards protect the government.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Following false rumors on the executions of Nodar Giorgadze and Jemal Koteliani, two members of the government imprisoned in the bunker by Gamsakhurdia, the Military Council draws up plans to launch a new attack against the Parliament.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 4 January, while Jaba Ioseliani announces a plan to abolish the presidency and institute a parliamentary system in Georgia, the Ministry of Internal Affairs and the Prosecutor General's Office pledge allegiance to the Military Council.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In response, governmental forces attack the Prosecutor's office, injuring two but failing to occupy the building.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Another combat takes place during the night when pro-Gamsakhurdia troops attempt to take over the television broadcasting tower with grenade-launchers, but fail to win this fight as well.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] These skirmishes, however, take place while the opposition manages to block all radio transmissions coming from the bunker and ceases fire on the Parliament building to allow troops to flee from the bunker.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Another demonstration of around 2,000 Gamsakhurdia supporters takes place on 5 January, during which protesters listen to speeches in favor of the president, before advancing in the street chanting the head of state's name.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While rumors of masked men approaching in cars create tensions within the group, the demonstration takes place peacefully and disperses itself naturally within a few hours.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The same day, the last fighting between the Military Council's forces and those of Gamsakhurdia take place.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While the residents leave massively the center of Tbilisi, Tengiz Kitovani wins a new fight on the Zulabashvili Brothers Street, behind the Parliament building, finalizing the surrounding of the last government stronghold.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Tengiz Sigua, meanwhile, announces publicly that one of his biggest critiques toward Gamsakhurdia is the latter's hostility toward Russia and predicts that Georgia will rejoin the Commonwealth of Independent States once Gamsakhurdia is gone.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 5 January, Russian newspaper *Postfactum* publishes an interview with an anonymous presidential guard that accuses the president of having forbidden any escape of his troops, threatening any soldier attempting to flee with execution.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Loyalist troops attempt one last time to take on the Broadcasting Tower of Tbilisi.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] At 20:12, the Military Council launches a last violent attack on the Parliament building, isolating Zviad Gamsakhurdia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The latter receives then an asylum offer from the Armenian president via telegram.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] At the end of 5 January, at least 90 dead and 700 injured are recorded by the Ministry of Health, while the Military Council insists that the number of victims goes as high as 200 dead and 900 injured.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The president and his family leave in the presidential car, a Mercedes-Benz, and, followed by an all-terrain vehicle, a minibus, and two Zhigulis, escape a roadblock installed along the Mtkvari river by Giorgi Shengelia, Vakhtang Kikabadze, and Giorgi Khaindrava.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Opposition forces penetrate then into the abandoned and ruined Parliament, some supporting columns of which are entirely destroyed.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Some Ikarus buses leave the Parliament with loyalist troops shortly after the president's departure, but these do not manage to leave the city in time and are caught in an ambush on Leselidze Street, during which six loyalist soldiers are executed by orders of Karkarashvili.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Those that remained inside the Parliament building, led by interim Parliament chairman Nemo Burchuladze, are captured.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] A last fight takes place in the western part of Tbilisi, near the Murkhatberdani Cemetery, in the afternoon.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Once calm is restored, an anti-mining squad is sent into the bunker to clean the area.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] According to opposition forces, Zviad Gamsakhurdia left Tbilisi with some 700 million rubles from the state treasury.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In exile, Zviad Gamsakhurdia crosses the Azerbaijani border at 09:20 and, escorted by 12 vehicles, arrives in Gandzha at 12:15.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Helicopters are deployed by the Military Council to search for the fleeing President, while Tengiz Kitovani spreads false rumors about the capture of Gamsakhurdia by Azerbaijani authorities, rumors soon denied by the Military Council's Ministry of Defense.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While some reports show that the exiled Georgians are attempting to reach Baku before crossing the Russian border into Daghestan, Gamsakhurdia ends up in the Armenian town of Idzhevan, in northern Armenia, with a following of 150, in the evening.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Kitovani and Sigua sign then a declaration announcing the fall of the "dictatorship" and several soldiers are seen celebrating on the fallen Parliament's steps.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In Tbilisi, the center of the city is entirely destroyed.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Ministry of Communications, the Tbilisi Hotel, the National Art Gallery, the Rustaveli Avenue Cinema, and other national emblems are ruined, while the Artists' House is full of bullet holes and even houses a rocket that never exploded and that would stay on site for several days.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Rustaveli Avenue itself is filled with broken windows, fallen trees, and burnt cars.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Metekhi Bridge, the main communication point between both sides of the Mtkvari river, is set on fire by Mkhedrioni soldiers.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Eduard Shevardnadze, former communist leader of Georgia and last Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union, announces his intention to return to Georgia in order to assist the Military Council and, according to American geopolitical analyst Thomas L.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Bush administration didn't know what to say, and so they said nothing." At the end of the conflict, official estimates show 90 dead and hundreds of injured, but contemporary MIA sources now show the total number of dead to be 113 Georgians.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] During the coup, the Zviad Gamsakhurdia government continues to assemble inside the bunker.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Almost the entire cabinet is present, as well as a majority of members of Parliament.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The latter continues to function in an official manner, despite the absence of its chairman, Akaki Asatiani.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 2 January, the present members vote to require the presence of Asatiani in the bunker, giving him a deadline of 11:00 on 4 January, a deadline ignored by Asatiani, who instead asks for Gamsakhurdia's resignation.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Inside the bunker, conditions are deplorable.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] One fighter described the bunker during the conflict as "unsanitary".
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In order to prevent the spread of dysentery, soldiers are given regularly a cocktail of medications, while the poor food rations are described as "bad".
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Aggravating the sanitary conditions, dead soldiers are amassed in the bunker and, after Gamsakhurdia's departure, the Military Council reveals a room with dozens of corpses.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Under these conditions, some witnesses note that Zviad Gamsakhurdia's personality changed drastically.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Murman Omanidze, his minister of Foreign Affairs, described him as "detached from everything, because of the massive stress befallen on his shoulders.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Opposition prisoners are jailed in cells created specifically for the conflict and are under the supervision of the minister of trade.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Military Council claims after the coup that two prisoners were executed inside the bunker, but this claim was never verified by international press.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 3 January, Tengiz Kitovani claims being in possession of a video proving that children from a local orphanage were taken by force into the bunker to serve as unwilling hostages and prevent any violent attack by the opposition, a claim denied by Gamsakhurdia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Tbilisi, the largest city in the Caucasus, suffers largely during the coup.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] According to Murman Omanidze's testimony and Russian media coverage, 80% of the downtown area's building are destroyed in the battle, leading to a large number of refugees.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Red Cross establishes a station in the Iveria Hotel, less than 900 meters from the Parliament building, and a volunteer rescue service called Santeli (სანთელი, "candle") is formed to aid civilians affected by the conflict.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The level of criminality increases considerably during the two weeks of the conflict, with a large number of robberies and carjackings.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In some cases, armed men form roadblocks and force drivers to empty their gas tanks.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Moreover, the Military Council claims that gangs of armed partisans of Gamsakhurdia terrorize the population several times, a claim that the Russian newspaper *Postfactum* cannot confirm.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Gia Karkarashvili is appointed as military governor of Tbilisi on 2 January, in charge of preserving peace within the capital.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Karkarashvili's militia imposes strict rules on the population.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] A curfew prohibits anyone in the street at nighttime, while the Military Council-declared state of emergency authorizes the paramilitary group to arrest anyone walking in the street to inspect their identification documents, to testify as they are Gamsakhurdia supporters or not.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Only Tbilisi residents are allowed to stay within the city for more than 24 hours during the conflict, while others are given a one-day permit.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Daily services are also largely affected.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While the subterranean metro continues to function normally, other public transportation means are interrupted.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] An economic crisis affects Tbilisi as shopping centers are closed and markets lose supplies due to farmers remaining in the countryside.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Moreover, several neighborhoods suffer from electricity shortages.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Phone lines, cut as soon as the coup began by the Ministry of Communications, are reestablished on 4 January by the Military Council.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] During this time, newspapers stop being printed due to fears of attacks by pro-Gamsakhurdia partisans.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Postal offices and telegraphic stations are closed as well.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 9 January, Military Council Prime Minister Tengiz Sigua held a press conference where he detailed the total damages caused by the coup d'état.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] According to him, a total of 10,000 square meters of housing were burnt down, leading to 252 families (759 people) becoming homeless, for which two hotels, two sanatoriums, and some state-owned dachas outside of Tbilisi were set aside as temporary housing.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The total cost of the damages was estimated to be between 500 million and 1 billion rubles.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 7 January, Zviad Gamsakhurdia proclaims his government to be in exile, insisting that his legitimacy remains valid and the coup cannot be recognized by the international community.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In order to demonstrate their support over the deposed president, a crowd of several hundreds of protesters demonstrate in the streets of Tbilisi the same day, ignoring the Military Council's decrees.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Jaba Ioseliani orders his troops to intimidate the crowd by shooting blanks, dispersing the demonstration and injuring two.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Several volunteers in Tbilisi and Mingrelia, Gamsakhurdia's native region, begin to organize and recruit armed supports to plan a counter-attack.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 13 January, a second delegation, chaired by Eldar Shengelia and including Chabua Amirejibi, Grigol Lortkipanidze, Giorgi Khaindrava, Vakhtang Kikabadze, and Rivaz Kipiani, go to Yerevan to meet with Armenian president Levon Ter-Petrosyan and National Assembly chair Babken Ararktsyan.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] However, the latter two refuse to extradite Gamsakhurdia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Lortkipanidze, one of the Georgian delegates, pens a letter signed by a dozen members of the Tbilisi intelligentsia asking for solidarity from the Armenian intelligentsia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Tengiz Kitovani went ahead to claim that "His [Gamsakhurdia's] return may provoke civil war in Georgia and in that case the Armenian leadership will share the blame".
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The same day, Zviad Gamsakhurdia and his family take a private plane with a Georgian pilot and leave Armenia for Grozny, the capital of Ichkeria, whose president, Dzhokhar Dudayev, still recognized the legitimacy of the government in exile.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Two fighter jets, sent by the Military Council, attempt to force the plane down, but fail.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Besides the temporary destruction of the downtown district of Tbilisi and the death of more than one hundred Georgians, the consequences of the December 1991–January 1992 civil conflict will be felt throughout the 1990s.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Military Council, in power in Tbilisi for another two months, creates an authoritarian and military regime across the country, until the arrival of Eduard Shevardnadze in March.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The latter, who had already announced his support of the opposition and his offer to come to Georgia's aid since 5 January, becomes the new head of state and has to spend several years to establish his central power, facing the militaristic ambitions of both Tengiz Kitovani and Jaba Ioseliani.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] It's only in 1995 that the next presidential elections are held and formalize Shevardnadze's leadership.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Gamsakhurdia's departure marks only the beginning of a civil war that would plunge Georgia into chaos until 1994.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] After a few months, Gamsakhurdia returns to Georgia through Abkhazia, setting up camp in Zugdidi, Mingrelia's regional capital.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] After having expelled the new central government's forces, Gamsakhurdia and his supporters, who are called "Zviadists", establish an opposing government in Western Georgia, pushing Mingrelia into a civil war until his death on 31 December 1993.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Throughout the 1990s, Mingrelia would become the target of violent political persecutions orchestrated by the Mkhedrioni militia to fight against the remaining Zviadists.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] An even more direct consequence is the situation unveiling in South Ossetia during the conflict.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] While the region is in the midst of a war against the Ossetian separatists, the coup gives the rebels the opportunity to strengthen their position.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Gamsakhurdia and his opposition recall one after the other their Georgian militias stationed in South Ossetia, giving a clear advantage to Ossetian soldiers.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] As a show of good faith, Kitovani and Ioseliani free Torez Kulumbegov, the former Soviet leader of the South Ossetian Autonomous Oblast imprisoned by Gamsakhurdia during the beginning of the Ossetian rebellion, on 5 January.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] This opening is, however, ignored by the Ossetians and the self-proclaimed Supreme Soviet of South Ossetia announces a general mobilization of all men aged 18 to 60 to use the Georgian setback at their advantage.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] A defense committee made of ten mobile units is formed on 5 January to defend Tskhinvali and attack Georgian positions.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] During that winter, Ossetians capture all of Tskhinvali and several villages.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Moreover, they use the instability in Georgia to hold the referendum on secession from Georgia, although Georgian population of the region is unable to participate and the referendum is not recognized by the new Georgian government.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The separatists' victory would be confirmed during a ceasefire signed by Shevardnadze in June 1992.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] As of today, South Ossetia remains under the separatists' control, although internationally mostly unrecognized.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The Tbilisi War remains a difficult memory for much of the capital's population.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Serge Schmemann, who covered the post-Soviet world for *The New York Times*, talks of a Georgian tragedy that forced "Georgian national heroes against Georgian national heroes." Thomas L.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] The American reaction toward the putsch shocked several Georgians who had been convinced that the United States represented Russia's geopolitical alternative.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] Gamsakhurdia himself in 1992 accused Bush and Yeltsin working together against his government, while denouncing James Baker for directly participating in the coup.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] On 11 March 2005, the Georgian Parliament adopted a resolution calling the 1991–1992 events a "violent and anti-constitutional military coup".
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] In 2008, Georgian president Mikheil Saakashvili accused Tengiz Kitovani of operating as a Russian "agent" during the civil conflict.
[src:abkhazia/1991-1992-georgian-coup-d-état-p02] According to 2020 poll by the Caucasus Research Resource Centers, 76% of Georgians think that the coup was a bad thing for Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-abkhazian-supreme-soviet-election] Supreme Soviet elections were held in Abkhazia on 29 September 1991, with a second round on 14 October.
[src:abkhazia/1991-abkhazian-supreme-soviet-election] A third round was held in twelve constituencies where voter turnout had been below the 50% threshold on 1 December.
[src:abkhazia/1991-abkhazian-supreme-soviet-election] The 65 seats in the Supreme Soviet were allocated to different ethnic groups; 28 were reserved for Abkhazians, 26 for Georgians and 11 for the other ethnic groups.
[src:abkhazia/1991-abkhazian-supreme-soviet-election] The Supreme Soviet was only able to approve legislation in some areas of policy with a 75% majority.
[src:abkhazia/1991-abkhazian-supreme-soviet-election] On 24 June 1992 the chairman of Abkhazian Supreme Soviet Vladislav Ardzinba ordered the republican guard to attack the building of Abkhazian Ministry of Internal Affairs and remove ethnic Georgian minister Givi Lominadze from office, which led to Lominadze's hospitalization.
[src:abkhazia/1991-abkhazian-supreme-soviet-election] Lominadze was replaced by Alexander Ankvab, a member of Abkhaz ethno-nationalist movement Aidgylara.
[src:abkhazia/1991-abkhazian-supreme-soviet-election] After this, on 30 June, Georgian deputies of the Supreme Soviet organized a walk-out and began boycotting the Soviet.
[src:abkhazia/1991-georgian-independence-referendum] An independence referendum was held in the Republic of Georgia on 31 March 1991.
[src:abkhazia/1991-georgian-independence-referendum] The referendum was sanctioned by the Georgian Supreme Council which was elected in the first multi-party elections held in Soviet Georgia in October 1990, and was dominated by a pro-independence bloc Round Table-Free Georgia led by the Soviet-era dissident Zviad Gamsakhurdia.
[src:abkhazia/1991-georgian-independence-referendum] The only question of the referendum asked: "Do you support the restoration of the independence of Georgia in accordance with the Act of Declaration of Independence of Georgia of May 26, 1918?" The official results showed over 99% in favor with a 90.6% voter turnout.
[src:abkhazia/1991-georgian-independence-referendum] Due to the ongoing ethnic discord, the polls were largely boycotted by the non-Georgian population in Abkhazia and South Ossetia, although local Georgian population of these regions participated in the vote.
[src:abkhazia/1991-georgian-independence-referendum] Four days after the final results were announced, the Georgian Supreme Council unanimously passed the declaration of independence on the second anniversary of the Soviet army crackdown on peaceful protests in Tbilisi on 9 April 1989.
[src:abkhazia/1991-georgian-independence-referendum] The referendum coincided with a private visit of the former U.S.
[src:abkhazia/1991-georgian-independence-referendum] President Richard Nixon who visited a few polling stations in Georgia’s capital Tbilisi before his departure to Moscow later that day.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] A referendum on the future of the Soviet Union was held on 17 March 1991 across the Soviet Union.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] It was the only national referendum in the history of the Soviet Union, although it was boycotted by authorities in six of the fifteen Soviet republics.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] The referendum asked whether to approve a new Union Treaty among the republics, to replace the 1922 treaty that created the USSR.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] In Kazakhstan, the wording of the referendum was changed by substituting "equal sovereign states" for "equal sovereign republics".
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] In Uzbekistan, Ukraine and Kirghizia additional questions were asked about sovereignty and independence of these republics.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] While the vote was boycotted by the authorities in Armenia, Estonia, Georgia (though not in the ASSRs of Abkhazia and South Ossetia), Latvia, Lithuania, and Moldova (though not in Transnistria and Gagauzia), turnout was 80% across the rest of the Soviet Union.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] The referendum's question was approved by nearly 80% of voters in all nine other republics that took part.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] However, the August coup attempt by hardliners of the Communist Party prevented the anticipated signing of the New Union Treaty that was due to take place the next day.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Although it failed, the coup attempt reduced confidence in Gorbachev's central government.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] It was followed by a series of referendums for independence in individual republics and led to the dissolution of the Soviet Union on 26 December 1991.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Do you consider it necessary to preserve the USSR as a renewed federation of equal sovereign republics, which will be fully ensured of human rights and freedoms of any nationality?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Считаете ли Вы необходимым сохранение Союза Советских Социалистических Республик как обновлённой федерации равноправных суверенных республик, в которой будут в полной мере гарантироваться права и свободы человека любой национальности?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Чи вважаєте ви за необхідне збереження Союзу Радянських Соціалістичних Республік як оновленої федерації рівноправних суверенних республік, у якій будуть повною мірою гарантуватися права і свободи людини будь-якої національності?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Ці лічыце вы неабходным захаванне СССР як абноўленай федэрацыі раўнапраўных суверэнных рэспублік, у якой будуць поўнасцю забяспечаны правы і свабоды чалавека любой нацыянальнасці?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Сиз СССРни ҳар қандай миллатнинг инсон ҳуқуқлари ва эркинликлари тўлиқ таъминланадиган тенг ҳуқуқли суверен республикаларнинг янгиланган федерацияси сифатида сақлаб қолишни зарур деб ҳисоблайсизми?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Кез келген ұлттың адам құқықтары мен бостандықтары толық қамтамасыз етілетін тең құқылы егеменді республикалардың жаңарған федерациясы ретінде КСРО-ны сақтау қажет деп санайсыз ба?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] თვლით თუ არა საჭიროდ სსრკ-ს შენარჩუნებას, როგორც თანაბარი სუვერენული რესპუბლიკების განახლებულ ფედერაციას, რომელიც სრულად იქნება უზრუნველყოფილი ნებისმიერი ეროვნების ადამიანის უფლებათა და თავისუფლებებით?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Истанилан миллатин инсан ҳүқуқ ва азадлықларыны там тамин эдаcак барабарҳүқуқлу суверен республикаларын јениланмиш федерасиясы кими ССРИ-ни қоруюб сахламағы зарури ҳесаб эдирсинизми?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Ar manote, kad būtina išsaugoti SSRS kaip atnaujintą lygių suverenių respublikų federaciją, kuriai bus visiškai užtikrintos bet kurios tautybės žmogaus teisės ir laisvės?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Консидераци че есте нечесарэ пэстрареа УРСС ка о федерацие реынноитэ де републичи суверане эгале, каре ва фи пе деплин асигуратэ де дрептуриле ши либертэциле омулуи де ориче националитате?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Vai uzskatāt par nepieciešamu saglabāt PSRS kā atjaunotu vienlīdzīgu suverēnu republiku federāciju, kurai tiks pilnībā nodrošinātas jebkuras tautības cilvēktiesības un brīvības?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Кандай гана улут болбосун адамдын укуктары жана эркиндиктери толук камсыз кылынуучу тец укуктуу суверендуу республикалардын жацыланган федерациясы катары СССРди сактап калуу зарыл деп эсептейсизби?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Оё шумо зарур мешуморед, ки СССР хамчун федерацияи навшудаи республикахои сохибихтиёри баробархукук нигох дошта шавад, ки он хукуку озодихои инсони хар миллат пурра таъмин карда мешавад?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Անհրաժե՞շտ եք համարում պահպանել ԽՍՀՄ-ը որպես իրավահավասար ինքնիշխան հանրապետությունների նորացված դաշնություն, որը լիովին կապահովվի ցանկացած ազգության մարդու իրավունքներով և ազատություններով?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Адам ҳукуклары ве ислендик миллетиң азатлыклары билен долы үпжүн эдилжек деңҳукуклы республикаларың тәзеленен федерациясы ҳөкмүнде СССР-и горап сакламагы зерур ҳасаплаярсыңызмы?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Kas peate vajalikuks säilitada NSV Liit kui võrdväärsete suveräänsete vabariikide uuendatud föderatsioon, millele on täielikult tagatud mis tahes rahvusest inimõigused ja vabadused?
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] On 24 December 1990, deputies of the 4th Congress of People's Deputies, having voted by name, decided to consider it necessary to preserve the USSR as a renewed federation of equal sovereign republics, which will be fully ensured human rights and freedoms of any nationality.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] For the adoption of the first resolution voted in 1553 deputies, against - 84, abstained - 70.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] For the adoption of the second resolution voted in 1677 deputies, against - 32, abstained - 66.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] However, concerning the first decision the Chairman YH Kalmykov later explained at a session of the Supreme Soviet of the USSR Supreme Council Committee for Legislation, the president asked to refrain from holding a referendum on the issue of private property.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] On 27 December 1990, Congress of People's Deputies of the USSR decided enact the law "On the popular vote (Soviet Union referendum)", effective immediately.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Article 5 of the Law specifies that the right to call a referendum belongs to the Congress of People's Deputies of the USSR, and on matters not related to the exclusive jurisdiction of the USSR Congress of People's Deputies, in the period between congresses – to the Supreme Soviet of the USSR.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] On 16 January 1991 the Supreme Council of USSR published Resolution 1910-1 "On the organization and measures to ensure the holding of a referendum of the USSR on the issue of preserving the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics".
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] An official referendum had been held in Estonia on 3 March 1991 on whether to restore the Estonian republic that had been occupied by the Soviet Union in 1940.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] The result was 77.8% in favour of restoring the Estonian republic.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Latvia also held an official referendum on 3 March 1991, when the overwhelming majority voted to restore the independent Latvian republic.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Lithuania had held a referendum on 9 February 1991, in which 93% of voters had approved independence.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Georgia was to hold its own independence referendum two weeks later, and Armenia on 21 September.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] In both cases, 99.5% of voters approved of the declarations of independence.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Consequently, in these republics, pro-Soviet front-organisations organised voluntary referendums without official sanction.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Turnout of voting here was considerably less than 50% of the franchised voters of these countries, but this information was not included in the official statement of the Central Commission of the Referendum of USSR.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] In several of the republics, additional questions were added to the ballot.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] In Russia, an additional question was asked on whether an elective post of the president of Russia should be created.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] In Kirghizia, Ukraine and Uzbekistan the additional question was on the sovereignty of their republics as part of a new union.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] In Kirghizia, voters were also asked "Do you agree that the Republic of Kirghizistan should be in the renewed Union as a sovereign republic with equal rights?" It was approved by 62.2% of voters, although turnout was lower at 81.7%, compared to 92.9% in the Union-wide referendum.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] In Ukraine, voters were also asked "Do you agree that Ukraine should be part of a Union of Soviet sovereign states on the basis on the Declaration of State Sovereignty of Ukraine?" The proposal was approved by 81.7% of voters.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] At the same day a referendum in the Galician oblasts Ivano-Frankivsk, Lviv, and Ternopil asked the three regions of the USSR about the creation of independent state of Ukraine.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] 88% of the voters in this referendum supported Ukraine's independence.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] 8.5 months later, all of Ukraine held an independence referendum on 1 December, in which 92% voted for independence.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] In Uzbekistan, voters were also asked "Do you agree that Uzbekistan should remain part of a renewed Union (federation) as a sovereign republic with equal rights?" It was approved by 94.9% of voters, with a turnout of 95.5%.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] On 29 December 98% of Uzbeks would vote for full independence.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Following the referendum, an agreement between the Soviet central government and nine republics — known as the 9+1 agreement — was signed in Novo-Ogaryovo on 23 April 1991.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] The New Union Treaty that resulted would have converted the Soviet Union into a confederation of independent republics with a common president, foreign policy, and military.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] The New Union Treaty was fully prepared and scheduled to be signed on 20 August 1991, but the signing was prevented by the State Emergency Committee coup.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] The coup of August 1991 was timed specifically to prevent the signing of the treaty.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] After the coup failed by 21 August, Gorbachev returned to Moscow and reluctantly agreed to the dissolution of the Communist Party.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Boris Yeltsin then proceeded to abolish or take over the institutions of the Soviet Union.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Most Soviet republics subsequently adopted declarations of independence.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] Ukraine's independence referendum on 1 December 1991, in which 92% voted for independence, is widely considered the most immediate event that led to the collapse of the Soviet Union.
[src:abkhazia/1991-soviet-union-referendum] The Soviet Union formally dissolved on 26 December 1991.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] The **2006 Georgian–Russian espionage controversy** began when the Government of Georgia arrested four Russian officers on charges of espionage, on September 27, 2006.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] The Western and Georgian media sources report that relations between the two post-Soviet nations have significantly deteriorated after Georgia and NATO agreed to hold talks on closer relations.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] Russian-Georgian relations have largely been reported as tense after the November 2003 Rose Revolution in Georgia brought the pro-Western reformist leader Mikheil Saakashvili to power.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] The 2006 gas pipeline explosions and the Russian ban of Georgian wines and mineral waters were interpreted by many as the means of the Government of Russia's pressure on the Georgian leadership for the country's close ties with NATO and the United States.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] The recent disruption of the *Status quo ante* in the Kodori Valley in Abkhazia led to a further downturn in the already tensed Russian-Georgian relations.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] In July 2006, the Georgian police and security forces took control of the Kodori Valley, hitherto controlled by the local Georgian militias led by the defiant commander Emzar Kvitsiani.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] Georgian officials claimed that the Russian security services were behind the 2006 Kodori crisis, while Russian and Abkhaz authorities accused Georgia of violation of the previous ceasefire agreements by deploying an armed force in the Valley.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] In September 2006, the area was officially renamed *Upper Abkhazia* by the Georgian government and declared to be the "temporary administrative center" of Abkhazia until the conflict is resolved.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] Continuous anti-Russian statements by the Georgian government, such as the September 2006 speech by President Saakashvili in Poland, were interpreted by some Russian media sources as depicting Russia as the "barbarous tribe of Huns".
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] On April 16, 2009, the case was brought before the European Court of Human Rights.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] The hearing was for the admissibility of the State vs.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] State case, a rare occurrence in this court.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] On July 3, 2014, the ECHR ruled that Russia engaged in a systematic policy of arresting, detaining, and expelling Georgian nationals between September 2006 and January 2007, violating several articles of the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] On September 29, Sergey Ivanov, Russia's Defense Minister and Vice Premier, denounced Georgia as a "bandit" state, and accused the NATO members of arming Georgia in support to "military solution" to the country's secessionist conflicts.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] Vladimir Zhirinovsky, urged the government to exert economic and political pressure on Georgia, and consider military intervention.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] On September 30, the BBC reported Foreign Minister of Georgia Gela Bezhuashvili as saying that Georgia "expected Russia to honour the pullout agreement" and as accusing the Russian government of "trying to scare" Georgians.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] President Mikheil Saakashvili described the Russian government's reaction to the arrests as "hysteria".
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] President Putin said, on October 1, Georgia's arrest of four Russian army officers for spying was "an act of state terrorism with hostage-taking", a statement that was downplayed by Saakashvili as "an overreaction caused by nervousness that they have created by themselves".
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] Meanwhile, various international organizations are trying to defuse the diplomatic conflict between the two sides.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] On September 30, the European Union foreign policy chief Javier Solana spoke by telephone with Mikheil Saakashvili, urging him to find a rapid solution and offering assistance.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), to which both Georgia and Russia belong, appealed, on October 1, for both sides to open a dialogue and seek a peaceful solution to the dispute.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] The OSCE Chairman-in-Office Karel De Gucht said he was ready to travel to the region if needed and assist the conflicting sides to reduce the tensions.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] On October 16, the Russian newspaper *Versiya* published an interview with the Georgian Defense Minister, Irakli Okruashvili where the minister stated that Russia "would lose if the quarrel between the two countries escalates into a shooting war".
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] On the same day Yury Baluyevsky, the Chief of Staff of the Russian Armed Forces, responded that Russia does not plan a war with Georgia and warned about the "consequences of the provocation by the brash politician".
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] The deportation of Georgian immigrants from Russia amid the ongoing diplomatic crisis also aroused much controversy.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] According to Russian authorities, more than half of the Georgians in the country are working illegally.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] Following the Russian crackdown on Georgian-owned alleged criminal businesses and the tightening of visa criteria for Georgians, on October 6, 2006, about 136 Georgians accused of "immigration offences" were flown back to Georgia on board a Russian cargo plane.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] Several deportees, however, showed valid passports and Russian entry visas, as reported by Reuters.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] Vice-president of the Federal Migration Service of Russia, Mikhail Tyurkin, said that immigrants "head home, to their mothers and children" and termed the mission "humanitarian".
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] The Russian authorities are also claimed to have begun targeting ethnic Georgian celebrities living in Moscow, including the famed Georgian-Russian fiction novelist Grigory Chkhartishvili better known by his penname Boris Akunin.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] Akunin commented on the Russian radio station *Echo of Moscow* that his publisher had been questioned by tax authorities over the writer's finances.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] "I didn't think I would live to see ethnic cleansing in Russia," he said.
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] On October 6, the influential Russian human rights organization, Memorial condemned both sides of the dispute, accusing the government of Russia of "racial discrimination", and Georgia of "irresponsible policies".
[src:abkhazia/2006-georgian-russian-espionage-controversy] On October 7, a minor unsanctioned rally organized by opposition youth activists in support of the Georgians was dispersed and more than a dozen of its participants detained by Moscow police.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The region had autonomy as the Abkhaz Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic within the Georgian Soviet Socialist Republic at the time when the Soviet Union began to disintegrate in the late 1980s.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The political status of Abkhazia is the central issue of the Abkhazia conflict and Georgia–Russia relations.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia is formally recognised as an independent state by five UN member states (Russia, Venezuela, Nicaragua, Nauru, and Syria), with two other states having previously recognised but withdrawn their recognition (Tuvalu and Vanuatu).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The remainder of the international community recognises Abkhazia as *de jure* part of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Lacking effective control over the Abkhazian territory, Georgia maintains an Abkhaz government-in-exile.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Despite a 1994 ceasefire agreement and years of negotiations, the dispute remains unresolved.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The long-term presence of a United Nations Observer Mission and a Russian-led Commonwealth of Independent States peacekeeping force failed to prevent the flare-up of violence on several occasions.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In August 2008, Abkhaz and Russian forces fought the Russo-Georgian War against Georgian forces, which led to the formal recognition of Abkhazia by Russia, the annulment of the 1994 ceasefire agreement and the termination of the UN mission.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 23 October 2008, the Parliament of Georgia declared Abkhazia a Russian-occupied territory.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Russian name Абхазия (**Abkhaziya**) is adapted from the Georgian აფხაზეთი (**Apkhazeti**).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz name *Apsny* (Abkhaz: Аԥсны, IPA [apʰsˈnɨ]) is etymologised as 'a land of the soul'; however, the literal meaning is 'a country of mortals'.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] It possibly first appeared in the seventh century in an Armenian text, perhaps referring to the ancient Apsilians.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In early Muslim sources, the term *Abkhazia* was generally used to mean the territory of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Presumably considered as a successor of the Kingdom of *Laziǩa* (*Egrisi* in Georgian sources), this new polity continued to be referred to as *Egrisi* in some Byzantine era Georgian and Armenian chronicles (e.g.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] *The Vitae of the Georgian Kings* by Leonti Mroveli and *History of Armenia* by Hovhannes Draskhanakerttsi).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Constitution of Abkhazia says the names of the "Republic of Abkhazia" and "Apsny" are equivalent and interchangeable.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Before the 20th century, the region was sometimes referred to in English language sources as *Abhasia*.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Between the 9th and 6th centuries BC, the territory of modern Abkhazia was part of the ancient Kingdom of Colchis.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Around the 6th century BC, the Greeks established trade colonies along the Black Sea coast of present-day Abkhazia, in particular at Pitiunt and Dioscurias.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Classical authors described various peoples living in the region and the great multitude of languages they spoke.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Arrian, Pliny and Strabo have given accounts of the Abasgoi and Moschoi peoples somewhere in modern Abkhazia on the eastern shore of the Black Sea.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] This region was subsequently absorbed in 63 BC into the Kingdom of *Laziǩa*.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] According to an Eastern tradition, Simon the Zealot died in Abkhazia during a missionary trip and was buried in Nicopsis; his mortal remains were later transferred to Anacopia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Roman Empire conquered Lazica in the 1st century AD; however, the Roman presence was confined to port cities.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] According to Arrian, the Abasgoi and Apsilae peoples were nominal Roman subjects, and there was a small Roman outpost in Dioscurias.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abasgoi likely served in the Roman army in *Ala Prima Abasgorum*, which was stationed in Egypt.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] After the 4th century Lazica regained a measure of independence, but remained within the Byzantine Empire's sphere of influence.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Anacopia was the principality's capital.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The country was mostly Christian, with the archbishop's seat in Pityus.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Stratophilus, the Metropolitan of Pityus, participated in the First Council of Nicaea in 325.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Around the middle of the 6th century AD, the Byzantines and the neighbouring Sassanid Persia fought for supremacy over Abkhazia, a conflict known as the Lazic War.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] During the war the Abasgians revolted against the Byzantine Empire and requested Sasanian assistance; the revolt was suppressed by General Bessas.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] An Arab incursion into Abasgia, led by Marwan II, was repelled by Prince Leon I jointly with his Lazic and Iberian allies in 736.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Leon I then married Mirian's daughter and a successor, King Leon II exploited this dynastic union to acquire Lazica in the 770s.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The successful defence against the Arab Caliphate, and new territorial gains in the east gave the Abasgian princes enough power to claim more autonomy from the Byzantine Empire.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Circa 778, Prince Leon II, with the help of the Khazars, declared independence from the Byzantine Empire and transferred his residence to Kutaisi.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] During this period the Georgian language replaced Greek as the language of literacy and culture.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Kingdom of Abkhazia flourished between 850 and 950 AD, which ended by unification of Abkhazia and eastern Georgian states under a single Georgian monarchy ruled by King Bagrat III at the end of the 10th century and the beginning of the 11th century.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] During the reign of Queen Tamar, Georgian chronicles mention Otagho as the Eristavi of Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] He was one of the first representatives of the House of Shervashidze (also known as Chachba) which went on to rule Abkhazia until the 19th century.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the 1240s, Mongols divided Georgia into eight military-administrative sectors (tümens).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The territory of contemporary Abkhazia formed part of the tümen administered by Tsotne Dadiani.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the 16th century, after the break-up of the Georgian Kingdom into small kingdoms and principalities, the Principality of Abkhazia (nominally a vassal of the Kingdom of Imereti) emerged, ruled by the Shervashidze dynasty.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In 1453, the Ottomans first attacked Sukhumi, and in the 1570s, they had a garrison there.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Throughout the 17th century, they continued to launch attacks, leading to the imposition of tribute on Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Ottoman influence grew significantly in the 18th century with the construction of a fort in Sukhumi, accompanied by a conversion of the rulers of Abkhazia and many other Abkhaz to Islam.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Nonetheless, conflicts between the Abkhaz and Turks persisted.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The spread of Islam in Abkhazia was first evidenced by the Ottoman traveller Evliya Çelebi in 1641.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Despite this, the Islamisation was more evident in the higher levels of society rather than the general population.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In his work, Çelebi also wrote that the principal tribe of the Abkhazian principality, Chách, spoke the Mingrelian language, a subset of Kartvelian (Georgian) languages.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia sought protection from the Russian Empire in 1801 but was declared "an autonomous principality" by the Russians in 1810.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Russia then annexed Abkhazia in 1864, and Abkhaz resistance was quashed as the Russians deported Muslim Abkhaz to Ottoman territories.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the beginning of the 19th century, while the Russians and Ottomans were vying for control of the region, the rulers of Abkhazia shifted back and forth across the religious divide.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The first attempt to enter into relations with Russia was made by Prince Kelesh-Bey in 1803, shortly after the incorporation of eastern Georgia into the expanding Tsarist empire in 1801.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] However, pro-Ottoman sympathy in Abkhazia prevailed for a short time after Kelesh-Bey was assassinated by his son, Aslan-Bey, in 1801.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 2 July 1810, Russian Marines stormed Sukhum-Kale and had Aslan-Bey replaced with his rival and brother, Sefer Ali-Bey, who had converted to Christianity and assumed the name of George.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia joined the Russian Empire as an autonomous principality, in 1810.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] However, Sefer-bey's rule was limited and many mountain regions were as independent as before.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The next Russo-Turkish war (1828–1829) strongly enhanced the Russian positions, leading to a further split in the Abkhaz elite, mainly along religious divisions.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] During the Crimean War (1853–1856), Russian forces had to evacuate Abkhazia and Prince Hamud-Bey Sharvashidze-Chachba (Mikhail), who ruled from 1822 to 1864, seemingly switched to the Ottomans.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Later on, the Russian presence strengthened and the highlanders of Western Caucasia were finally subjugated by Russia in 1864.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Later that same year, Abkhazia was incorporated into the Russian Empire as a special military province of Sukhum-Kale which was transformed, in 1883, into an *okrug* as part of the Kutaisi Governorate.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Large numbers of Muslim Abkhazians, said to have constituted as much as 40% of the Abkhazian population, emigrated to the Ottoman Empire between 1864 and 1878 together with other Muslim populations of the Caucasus, a process known as *Muhajirism*.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Large areas of the region were left uninhabited and many Armenians, Georgians, Russians and others subsequently migrated to Abkhazia, resettling much of the vacated territory.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Some Georgian historians assert that Georgian tribes (Svans and Mingrelians) had populated Abkhazia since the time of the Colchis kingdom.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Russian government had plans to colonize Abkhazia with Russian settlers, and created a special legal framework granting land allocations to Russians to encourage their migration.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] However, the Russian colonization efforts failed because of the lack of roads connecting Abkhazia to the main economic centers in Southern Russia, the unfamiliarity of the Russian settlers with local climate and agriculture, and their high susceptibility to malaria (leading to some deaths).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] This led to the other ethnic groups, which the Russian government did not plan to be settled in Abkhazia, to migrate spontaneously and outnumber the Russians in the region.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] This included former Ottoman subjects, such as Greeks and Armenians, and Mingrelians from the neighboring province within the empire.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Both were more familiar with the local climate and were less susceptible to malaria.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Mingrelians became the largest group of arrivals, despite being marginalized as an agricultural labor force due to the lack of state support and legal restrains placed on them.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Their arrival alarmed the Russian authorities, because they saw the Mingrelian migration as an impediment to the Russian colonization, and the Russian government responded with the legal measures to restrict the settlement of Mingrelians in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The same policy was conducted to alienate Abkhazians from Georgians despite their common historical heritage and few problems historically.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the case of the Abkhaz, Russia attempted to obviate the use of the Georgian language by Abkhazians which they previously wielded as the second language and used for the literacy and high culture.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Instead, the Russian authorities put an effort to substitute Georgian with the Russian language.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] A separate Abkhaz alphabet was created based on Cyrillic script and the teaching of the Russian language to Abkhazians was mandated.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] By official decision of the Russian authorities, the residents of Abkhazia and Samurzakano had to study and pray in Russian.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] After the mass deportation of 1878, Abkhazians were left in the minority, officially branded "guilty people", and had no leader capable of mounting serious opposition to Russification.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 17 March 1898, the synodal department of the Russian Orthodox Church of Georgia-Imereti, by Order 2771, again prohibited teaching and the conduct of religious services in Georgian.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Mass protests by the Georgian population of Abkhazia and Samurzakano followed, news of which reached the Russian emperor.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 3 September 1898 the Holy Synod issued Order 4880, which decreed that those parishes where the congregation was Mingrelian (i.e.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Georgian), conduct both church services and church education in Georgian, while Abkhazian parishes use old Slavic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the Sukhumi district, this order was carried out in only three of 42 parishes.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Tedo Sakhokia demanded the Russian authorities introduce Abkhazian and Georgian languages in church services and education.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The official response was a criminal case brought against Tedo Sakhokia and leaders of his "Georgian Party" active in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In 1904, the territory of Gagra District was detached from Sukhumi okrug and joined to the Black Sea Governorate after Duke Alexander of Oldenburg, a member of the Russian royalty, built a resort there.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] By the early 20th century, the Georgians, represented by Samurzakanians and Mingrelians, were the largest group in Abkhazia, but from the social point of view, they were the most disadvantaged and marginalized group, being agricultural workers with severe restrictions on their residential status.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz and the Russians were the well-off groups which controlled large amounts of land and were well-represented in the nobility and bureaucracy.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Armenians and Greeks were mostly involved in the tobacco industry.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Following the October Revolution in Russia, the Transcaucasian Commissariat was set up in Southern Caucasus, which gradually took steps towards the independence.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Transcaucasia declared its independence from Russia on 9 April 1918 as a federative republic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 8 May 1918, the Bolsheviks seized power in Abkhazia and disbanded the local Abkhaz People's Council.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] It requested aid from the Transcausian authorities, which dispatched the Georgian People's Guard and defeated the rebels on 17 May.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 26 May 1918, Georgia declared independence from the Transcaucasian Federation, which dissolved on 28 May.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 8 June 1918, the Abkhaz People's Council signed a treaty with the Georgian National Council, which confirmed Abkhazia's status as an autonomy within the Georgian Democratic Republic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Georgian army defeated another Bolshevik rebellion in the region.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] It remained part of Georgia after another Bolshevik revolt and a Turkish expedition were defeated in 1918.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Russian general and a leader of White movement Anton Denikin laid claims on Abkhazia and captured Gagra, but the Georgians counter-attacked in April 1919 and retook the city.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Denikin's Volunteer Army was eventually defeated by the Red Army, and Bolshevik Russia signed an agreement with Georgia in May 1920, recognising Abkhazia as a part of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In 1919, a first election was held to the Abkhaz People's Council.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Council favoured being an autonomous region within Georgia, and it lasted until the Red Army invasion of Georgia in February 1921.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 20 March 1919, the newly elected Abkhazian People's Council adopted the "Act on Abkhazian Autonomy", which formalised the establishment of the Abkhazian Autonomy within the Georgian Democratic Republic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In 1921, the Bolshevik Red Army invaded Georgia and ended its short-lived independence.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia was made a Socialist Soviet Republic (SSR Abkhazia) with the ambiguous status of a "*treaty republic"* associated with the Georgian SSR.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Under the *korenizatsiia* policy of the Soviet Union, the Abkhaz people were not considered the "advanced" people, and thus saw an increased focus on their national language and cultural development.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Under this nationalities policy, the Abkhaz received various benefits such as schooling in their language; the official literary language was established for the first time.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Between 1922 and 1926, the share of Abkhazes increased from 19.8% to 27.8% of the population (possibly due to the immigration of ethnic Abkhaz from Turkey or re-identification as Abkhaz).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Their share among the members of the local communist party grew from 10% to the 25%.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Meanwhile, the proportion of the ethnic Georgian population decreased from 42% in 1922 to 36% in 1926, while their proportion in the local communist party also decreased from 40% to 33%.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The report noted that all major posts were held by the Abkhaz, they were overrepresented in the local structures such as the police, and the local Komsomol was only admitting ethnic Abkhazians.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In 1931, Joseph Stalin made Abkhazia an autonomous republic (Abkhaz ASSR) within the Georgian SSR.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the Terror of 1937–38, the ruling elite was purged of Abkhazes and by 1952 over 80% of the 228 top party and government officials and enterprise managers were ethnic Georgians; there remained 34 Abkhazes, 7 Russians, and 3 Armenians in these positions.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Georgian Communist Party leader Kandid Charkviani supported the Georgianization of Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Starting from 1939, peasant households from the rest of the Georgian SSR were resettled to Abkhazia which changed its demographic makeup significantly.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Georgians were the largest ethnic group in Abkhazia even before Stalin's policies.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The publishing of materials in Abkhazian dwindled and was eventually stopped altogether; Abkhaz schools were closed in 1945–1946, requiring Abkhaz children to study in the Georgian language.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The teaching of the Abkhaz language was preserved in the new reorganised Abkhaz schools as a mandatory subject by the decision of the Georgian Communist Party.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The policy of repression was eased after Stalin's death and Beria's execution, and the Abkhaz were given a greater role in the governance of the republic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] As in most of the smaller autonomous republics, the Soviet government encouraged the development of culture and particularly of literature.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhazian ASSR was the only autonomous republic in the USSR in which the language of the titular nation (in that case Abkhaz) was confirmed in its constitution as one of its official languages.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the post-war period, the Abkhazian ASSR was dominated by the ethnic Abkhazes, who occupied many more positions in the autonomous republic compared to Georgians.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] During the late Soviet period, ethnic Abkhazes occupied 41% of the seats in Abkhazian Supreme Soviet, and 67% of the republican ministers were ethnically Abkhaz.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Moreover, they held even larger proportion of lower level official posts within the autonomous republic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The first secretary of the communist party in Abkhazia was also ethnically Abkhaz.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] All of this was despite the fact that Abkhazians made up only 17.8% of the region's population, while Georgians made up 45.7%, and other ethnicities (Greeks, Russians, Armenians, etc.) made up 36.5%.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] As the Soviet Union began to disintegrate at the end of the 1980s, ethnic tensions grew between the Abkhaz and Georgians over Georgia's moves towards independence.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Many Abkhaz opposed this, fearing that an independent Georgia would lead to the elimination of their autonomy, and argued instead for the establishment of Abkhazia as a separate Soviet republic in its own right.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] With the onset of perestroika, the agenda of Abkhaz nationalists became more radical and exclusive.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In 1988, they began to ask for the reinstatement of Abkhazia's former status of Union Republic, as the submission of Abkhazia to another Union Republic was not considered to give enough guarantees of their development.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] They justified their request by referring to the Leninist tradition of the right of nations to self-determination, which they asserted was violated when Abkhazia's sovereignty was curtailed in 1931.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In June 1988, a manifesto defending Abkhaz distinctiveness (known as the Abkhazian Letter) was sent to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Georgian–Abkhaz dispute turned violent on 16 July 1989 in Sukhumi.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Numerous Georgians were killed or injured when they tried to enroll in a Georgian university instead of an Abkhaz one.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] After several days of violence, Soviet troops restored order in the city.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In March 1990, Georgia declared sovereignty, unilaterally nullifying treaties concluded by the Soviet government since 1921 and thereby moving closer to independence.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Most ethnic non-Georgians in Abkhazia later boycotted a 31 March referendum on Georgia's independence, which was supported by a huge majority of Georgian population.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Within weeks, Georgia declared independence on 9 April 1991, under former Soviet dissident Zviad Gamsakhurdia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Under Gamsakhurdia, the situation was relatively calm in Abkhazia and a power-sharing agreement was soon reached between the Abkhaz and Georgian factions, granting to the Abkhaz a certain over-representation in the local legislature.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Under the compromise solution negotiated in August 1991, the Abkhaz received an ethnic quota of 28 seats in the Abkhazian Supreme Soviet, despite being only 18% of the population.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Georgians, making up 46% of the population, got 26 seats, while the rest received 11 seats.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] A two-thirds majority was to be required to pass constitutional changes to ensure that key decisions would not be taken without approval from both Abkhaz and Georgian deputies and each side would hold veto power in principle.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The elections using this scheme were held in late 1991.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Gamsakhurdia's rule was soon challenged by armed opposition groups, under the command of Tengiz Kitovani, that forced him to flee the country in a military coup in January 1992.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Gamsakhurdia was replaced by former Soviet Georgian leader and Soviet foreign minister Eduard Shevardnadze, who became the country's head of state.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 21 February 1992, Georgia's ruling military council announced that it was abolishing the Soviet-era constitution and restoring the 1921 Constitution of the Democratic Republic of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Many Abkhaz interpreted this as an abolition of their autonomous status, although the 1921 constitution contained a provision for the region's autonomy.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 23 July 1992, the Abkhaz faction in the republic's Supreme Soviet declared effective independence from Georgia, although the session was boycotted by ethnic Georgian deputies and the gesture went unrecognised by any other country.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz leadership launched a campaign of ousting Georgian officials from their offices, a process which was accompanied by violence.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the meantime, the Abkhaz leader Vladislav Ardzinba intensified his ties with hardline Russian politicians and military elite and declared he was ready for a war with Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] To respond to this situation, Eduard Shevardnadze, new leader of Georgia, interrupted his trip to Western Georgia, where he was touring cities still supporting ousted Gamsakhurdia and was being met by heckling.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Shevardnadze announced that the decision of the Abkhaz faction was "absolutely unexpected" and that it was made without considering the opinion of the majority of population in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In August 1992, the National Guard of Georgia, led by Tengiz Kitovani entered in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The declared goal was to free Georgian officials held captive in Abkhazia, and to reopen the railway line running through Abkhazia to the rest of Georgia, which was frequently robbed.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] According to Darrell Slider, Abkhaz troops were the first to open fire.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] This led to the beginning of the War in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhaz separatist government retreated to Gudauta where the Russian military base was located.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees reported the ethnic-based violence against Georgians in Gudauta.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz were relatively unarmed at the time and the Georgian troops were able to march into the capital Sukhumi with relatively little resistance and subsequently engaged in ethnically based pillage, looting, assault, and murder.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] They sided with the Abkhaz separatists to fight against the Georgian government.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Russian military did not impede the crossing of the Russia-Georgia border by the North Caucasian militants into Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the case of Basayev, it has been suggested that when he and the members of his battalion came to Abkhazia, they received training by the Russian Army (though others dispute this), presenting another possible motive.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On September 25, 1992, Russian Supreme Council (parliament) passed a resolution which condemned Georgia, supported Abkhazia and called for the suspension of the delivery of any weapons and equipment to Georgia and the deployment of a Russian peacekeeping force in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] It was sponsored by a Russian nationalist politician Sergei Baburin, a Russian deputy who met Vladislav Ardzinba and argued that he was not that much sure that Abkhazia was part of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In October, the Abkhaz and North Caucasian paramilitaries mounted a major offensive against Gagra after breaking a cease-fire, which drove the Georgian forces out of large swathes of the republic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Shevardnadze's government accused Russia of giving covert military support to the rebels with the aim of "detaching from Georgia its native territory and the Georgia-Russian frontier land".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] 1992 ended with the rebels in control of much of Abkhazia northwest of Sukhumi.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The conflict was in stalemate until July 1993, when Abkhaz separatist militias launched an abortive attack on Georgian-held Sukhumi.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] They surrounded and heavily shelled the capital, where Shevardnadze was trapped.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The warring sides agreed to a Russian-brokered truce in Sochi at the end of July.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] But the ceasefire broke down again on 16 September 1993.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhaz forces, with armed support from outside Abkhazia, launched attacks on Sukhumi and Ochamchire.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Notwithstanding UN Security Council's call for the immediate cessation of hostilities and its condemnation of the violation of the ceasefire by the Abkhaz side, fighting continued.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] After ten days of heavy fighting, Sukhumi was taken by Abkhazian forces on 27 September 1993.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Shevardnadze narrowly escaped death, after vowing to stay in the city no matter what.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] He changed his mind, however, and decided to flee when separatist snipers fired on the hotel where he was staying.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhaz, North Caucasian militants, and their allies committed numerous atrocities against the city's remaining ethnic Georgians, in what has been dubbed the Sukhumi Massacre.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The mass killings and destruction continued for two weeks, leaving thousands dead and missing.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz forces quickly overran the rest of Abkhazia as the Georgian government faced a second threat; an uprising by the supporters of the deposed Zviad Gamsakhurdia in the region of Mingrelia (Samegrelo).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Only a small region of eastern Abkhazia, the upper Kodori gorge, remained under Georgian control (until 2008).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] During the war, gross human rights violations were reported on both sides.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Georgian troops have been accused of having committed looting and murders "for the purpose of terrorising, robbing and driving the Abkhaz population out of their homes" in the first phase of the war (according to Human Rights Watch).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) Summits in Budapest (1994), Lisbon (1996) and Istanbul (1999) have recognized the ethnic cleansing of Georgians in Abkhazia in 1992-1993 by the Abkhaz forces and their allies.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] While both sides have committed atrocities, the Abkhaz side has been singled out as responsible for a deliberate displacement campaign "carried out as a military, strategic and political objective in its".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Before the 1992 War in Abkhazia, Georgians made up nearly half of Abkhazia's population, while less than one-fifth of the population was Abkhaz.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] As the war progressed, confronted with hundreds of thousands of ethnic Georgians who were unwilling to leave their homes, the Abkhaz separatists implemented the process of ethnic cleansing in order to expel and eliminate the Georgian ethnic population in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] About 5,000 were killed, 400 went missing and up to 250,000 ethnic Georgians were expelled from their homes.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] According to International Crisis Group, as of 2006 slightly over 200,000 Georgians remained displaced in Georgia proper.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The campaign of ethnic cleansing also included Russians, Armenians, Greeks, moderate Abkhaz and other minor ethnic groups living in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] More than 20,000 houses owned by ethnic Georgians were destroyed.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Hundreds of schools, kindergartens, churches, hospitals, and historical monuments were pillaged and destroyed.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Following the process of ethnic cleansing and mass expulsion, the population of Abkhazia was reduced from 525,000 in 1989 to 216,000 in 2012.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Pogroms against ethnic Georgians organised by Abkhaz leaders continued even after the end of war, as late as February 1995.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Of about 250,000 Georgian refugees, some 60,000 subsequently returned to Abkhazia's Gali District between 1994 and 1998, but tens of thousands were displaced again when fighting resumed in the Gali District in 1998.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Nevertheless, between 40,000 and 60,000 refugees have returned to the Gali District since 1998, including persons commuting daily across the ceasefire line and those migrating seasonally in accordance with agricultural cycles.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The human rights situation remained precarious for a while in the Georgian-populated areas of the Gali District.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Key officials of the Gali District are virtually all ethnic Abkhaz, though their support staff are ethnic Georgian.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The ethnic Georgians in Gali are deprived of voting rights: during the 2021 local elections, only 900 eligible voters were registered in the Gali district, despite the 30,259 residents in the area.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Presidential elections were held in Abkhazia on 3 October 2004.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Russia supported Raul Khajimba, the prime minister backed by the ailing outgoing separatist President Vladislav Ardzinba.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Posters of Russia's President Vladimir Putin together with Khajimba, who, like Putin, had worked as a KGB official, were everywhere in Sukhumi.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Deputies of Russia's parliament and Russian singers, led by Joseph Cobsohn, a State Duma deputy and a popular singer, came to Abkhazia, campaigning for Khajimba.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] However, Khajimba lost the elections to Sergei Bagapsh.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The tense situation in the republic led to the cancellation of the election results by the Supreme Court.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] After that, a deal was struck between former rivals to run jointly, with Bagapsh as a presidential candidate and Khajimba as a vice-presidential candidate.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] They received more than 90% of the votes in the new election.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In July 2006, Georgian forces launched a successful police operation against the rebelled administrator of the Georgian-populated Kodori Valley, Emzar Kvitsiani.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Kvitsiani had been appointed by the previous president of Georgia, Eduard Shevardnadze, and refused to recognise the authority of president Mikheil Saakashvili, who succeeded Shevardnadze after the Rose Revolution.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Although Kvitsiani escaped capture by Georgian police, the Kodori Gorge was brought back under the control of the central government in Tbilisi.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Sporadic acts of violence continued throughout the postwar years.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Despite the peacekeeping status of the Russian peacekeepers in Abkhazia, Georgian officials routinely claimed that Russian peacekeepers were inciting violence by supplying Abkhaz rebels with arms and financial support.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Russian support of Abkhazia became pronounced when the Russian ruble became the de facto currency and Russia began issuing passports to the population of Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Georgia has also accused Russia of violating its airspace by sending helicopters to attack Georgian-controlled towns in the Kodori Gorge.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In April 2008, a Russian MiG – prohibited from Georgian airspace, including Abkhazia – shot down a Georgian UAV.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 9 August 2008, Abkhazian forces fired on Georgian forces in Kodori Gorge.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] This coincided with the 2008 South Ossetia war where Russia decided to support the Ossetian separatists who had been attacked by Georgia after Russia provoked Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The conflict escalated into a full-scale war between the Russian Federation and the Republic of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 10 August 2008, an estimated 9,000 Russian soldiers entered Abkhazia ostensibly to reinforce the Russian peacekeepers in the republic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] About 1,000 Abkhazian soldiers moved to expel the residual Georgian forces within Abkhazia in the Upper Kodori Gorge.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] By 12 August the Georgian forces and civilians had evacuated the last part of Abkhazia under Georgian government control.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Russia recognised the independence of Abkhazia on 26 August 2008.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] This was followed by the annulment of the 1994 ceasefire agreement and the termination of UN and OSCE monitoring missions.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 28 August 2008, the Parliament of Georgia passed a resolution declaring Abkhazia a Russian-occupied territory.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Since independence was recognised by Russia, a series of controversial agreements were made between the Abkhazian government and the Russian Federation that leased or sold a number of key state assets and relinquished control over the borders.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In May 2009 several opposition parties and war veteran groups protested against these deals complaining that they undermined state sovereignty and risked "exchanging one colonial power [Georgia] for another [Russia]".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The vice-president, Raul Khajimba, resigned on 28 May saying he agreed with the criticism the opposition had made.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Subsequently, a conference of opposition parties nominated Raul Khajimba as their candidate in the December 2009 Abkhazian presidential election won by Sergei Bagapsh.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In the spring of 2014, the opposition submitted an ultimatum to President Aleksandr Ankvab to dismiss the government and make radical reforms.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On 27 May 2014, in the centre of Sukhumi, 10,000 supporters of the Abkhaz opposition gathered for a mass demonstration.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] On the same day, Ankvab's headquarters in Sukhumi was stormed by opposition groups led by Raul Khajimba, forcing him into flight to Gudauta.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The opposition claimed that the protests were sparked by poverty, but the main point of contention was President Ankvab's liberal policy towards ethnic Georgians in the Gali region.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The opposition said these policies could endanger Abkhazia's ethnic Abkhazian identity.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] After Ankvab fled the capital, on 31 May, the People's Assembly of Abkhazia appointed parliamentary speaker Valery Bganba as acting president, declaring Ankvab unable to serve.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] It also decided to hold an early presidential election on 24 August 2014.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Ankvab soon declared his formal resignation, although he accused his opponents of acting immorally and violating the constitution.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Raul Khajimba was later elected president, taking office in September 2014.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In November 2014, Vladimir Putin moved to formalise the Abkhazian military's relationship as part of the Russian armed forces, signing a treaty with Khajimba.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Georgian government denounced the agreement as "a step towards annexation".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Khajimba was re-elected with a margin of less than 2% in 2019.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] In January 2020 the Abkhazian Supreme Court annulled the results, following protests against Khajimba.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Khajimba resigned the presidency on 12 January, and new elections were called for 22 March.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Aslan Bzhania was elected in the subsequent elections with around 59% of the vote.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Protests took place in November 2024 after the arrest of five opposition activists who opposed an investment agreement with Russia, which led to the resignation of then–President Aslan Bzhania and a new presidential election in February 2025.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Acting president Badra Gunba was elected, receiving 56% of the vote.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia covers an area of about 8,665 km2 (3,346 sq mi) at the western end of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Caucasus Mountains to the north and northeast separate Abkhazia and the Russian Federation.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] To the east and southeast, Abkhazia is bounded by the Georgian region of Samegrelo-Zemo Svaneti; and on the south and southwest by the Black Sea.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia is diverse geographically with lowlands stretching to the extremely mountainous north.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Greater Caucasus Mountain Range runs along the region's northern border, with its spurs – the Gagra, Bzyb and Kodori ranges – dividing the area into a number of deep, well-watered valleys.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The highest peaks of Abkhazia are in the northeast and east and several exceed 4,000 metres (13,123 ft) above sea level.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia's landscape ranges from coastal forests and citrus plantations to permanent snows and glaciers in the north of the region.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Although Abkhazia's complex topographic setting has spared most of the territory from significant human development, its cultivated fertile lands produce tea, tobacco, wine and fruits, a mainstay of the local agricultural sector.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia is richly irrigated by small rivers originating in the Caucasus Mountains.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Chief of these are: Kodori, Bzyb, Ghalidzga, and Gumista.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The Psou River separates the region from Russia, and the Inguri serves as a boundary between Abkhazia and Georgia proper.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] There are several periglacial and crater lakes in mountainous Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Lake Ritsa is the most important of them.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Because of Abkhazia's proximity to the Black Sea and the shield of the Caucasus Mountains, the region's climate is very mild.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The coastal areas of the republic have a subtropical climate, where the average annual temperature in most regions is around 15 °C (59 °F), and the average January temperature remains above freezing.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The climate at higher elevations varies from maritime mountainous to cold and summerless.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Also, due to its position on the windward slopes of the Caucasus, Abkhazia receives high amounts of precipitation, though humidity decreases further inland.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The mountains of Abkhazia receive significant amounts of snow.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The world's deepest known cave, Veryovkina Cave, is located in Abkhazia's western Caucasus mountains.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The latest survey (as of March 2018) has measured the vertical extent of this cave system as 2,212 metres (7,257 ft) between its highest and lowest explored points.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The lowland regions used to be covered by swaths of oak, beech, and hornbeam, which have since been cleared.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] There are two main entrances into Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The southern entrance is at the Inguri bridge, a short distance from the city of Zugdidi.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] The northern entrance ("Psou") is in the town of Leselidze.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] Owing to the situation with a recognition controversy, many foreign governments advise their citizens against travelling to Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p01] According to President Raul Khajimba, over the summer of 2015, thousands of tourists visited Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Legislative powers are vested in the People's Assembly, which consists of 35 elected members.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The last parliamentary elections were held in March 2022.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Ethnicities other than Abkhaz (Armenians, Russians and Georgians) are claimed to be under-represented in the Assembly.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Most refugees from the 1992–1993 war (mainly ethnic Georgians) have not been able to return and have thus been excluded from the political process.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Some refugees have been allowed to return, in particular in the Gali district where 98% of the population is Georgian as it was before the ethnic cleansing, however, they have been stripped of the voting and other rights.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] As such, during the 2021 local elections, only 900 eligible voters were registered in the Gali district, despite the 30,259 residents in the area.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The territory of the Gali district has also been diminished through addition of some of its lands to Tkvarcheli and Ochamchire districts.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia has a major military and economic presence in Abkhazia, and the relationship between the two has been described as asymmetrical, with Abkhazia being heavily dependent on Russia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has adopted Russian technical and commercial standards, and large part of its infrastructure is owned by Russian companies, with Russia heavily investing in the military infrastructure.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The 2014 Treaty on Alliance and Strategic Partnership obliges Abkhazia to coordinate its foreign policy with Russia and merge the armed forces.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] As such, under pressure from Russia, Abkhazia joined Russia in imposing sanctions on Turkey in 2016, becoming Russia's only ally to do so.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazian officials have stated that they have given the Russian Federation the responsibility of representing their interests abroad.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Some have described Abkhazia as Russia's protectorate with a strong and one-sided dependence.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] According to a 2010 study published by the University of Colorado Boulder, the vast majority of Abkhazia's population supports independence, while a smaller number is in favour of joining the Russian Federation.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Support for reunification with Georgia is very low.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Among ethnic Abkhaz, explicit support for reunification with Georgia is around 1%; a similar figure can be found among ethnic Russians and Armenians as well.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] However, those supporting reunification with Georgia, including ethnic Abkhazians, have faced harassment by the separatist authorities in form of arrests and coercion to apologize publicly.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 2014, separatist Republic of Abkhazia and Russian Federation signed the "Treaty of Alliance and Strategic Partnership" with Russia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Based on this treaty, in November 2020, Abkhazia launched a programme on the "formation of common social and economic space" with Russia to make Abkhaz laws and administrative measures more similar to Russian ones in social, economic, health and political spheres.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] On 15 August 2024, the Russian Deputy Minister of Economic Development Dmitry Volvach said that the process of Abkhazia's harmonisation of its laws with Russia was "almost complete".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Government of the Autonomous Republic of Abkhazia is the government in exile that Georgia recognises as the legal government of Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] This pro-Georgian government maintained a foothold on Abkhazian territory, in the upper Kodori Valley from July 2006 until it was forced out by fighting in August 2008.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] This government is also partly responsible for the affairs of some 250,000 IDPs, forced to leave Abkhazia following the War in Abkhazia and ethnic cleansing that followed.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The current Head of the Government is Giorgi Jincharadze.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] During this period, the Government of Abkhazia in exile, led by Tamaz Nadareishvili, was known for a hard-line stance towards the Abkhaz problem and frequently voiced their opinion that the solution to the conflict can be attained only through Georgia's military response to secessionism.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Later, Nadareishvili's administration was implicated in some internal controversies and had not taken an active part in the politics of Abkhazia until a new chairman, Irakli Alasania, was appointed by President of Georgia, Mikheil Saakashvili, his envoy in the peace talks over Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Republic of Abkhazia is divided into seven raions (districts) named after their primary cities: Gagra, Gudauta, Sukhumi, Ochamchira, Gulripshi, Tkvarcheli and Gali.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] These districts remain mostly unchanged since the break-up of the Soviet Union, with the exception of the Tkvarcheli District, created in 1995 from parts of the Ochamchira and Gali districts.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The President of the Republic appoints districts' heads from those elected to the districts' assemblies.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] There are elected village assemblies whose heads are appointed by the districts' heads.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The administrative subdivisions under Georgian law are identical to the ones outlined above, except for the new Tkvarcheli district.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhazian Armed Forces are the military of the Republic of Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The basis of the Abkhazian armed forces was formed by the ethnically Abkhaz National Guard, which was established in early 1992.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Most of their weapons come from the former Russian airborne division base in Gudauta.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhazian military is primarily a ground force, but includes small sea and air units.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia deploys its own military units as part of the 7th Military Base in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] These units are reportedly subordinate to the Russian 49th Army and include both ground elements and air defence assets.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia, Transnistria, and South Ossetia are post-Soviet "frozen conflict" zones.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] These three states maintain friendly relations with each other and form the Community for Democracy and Rights of Nations.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia and Nicaragua officially recognised Abkhazia after the Russo-Georgian War.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Venezuela recognised Abkhazia in September 2009.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In December 2009, Nauru recognised Abkhazia, reportedly in return for $50 million in humanitarian aid from Russia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The unrecognised republic of Transnistria and the partially recognised republic of South Ossetia have recognised Abkhazia since 2006.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia is also a member of the Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization (UNPO).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] A majority of sovereign states recognise Abkhazia as an integral part of Georgia and support its territorial integrity according to the principles of international law, although Belarus has expressed sympathy toward the recognition of Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Some have officially noted Abkhazia as under occupation by the Russian military.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The United Nations has been urging both sides to settle the dispute through diplomatic dialogue and ratifying the final status of Abkhazia in the Georgian constitution.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] However, the Abkhaz *de facto* government considers Abkhazia a sovereign country even if it is recognised by few other countries.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhaz side, however, has never accepted the paper as a basis for negotiations.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Eventually, Russia also withdrew its approval of the document.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 2005 and 2008, the Georgian government offered Abkhazia a high degree of autonomy and possible federal structure within the borders and jurisdiction of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] On 18 October 2006, the People's Assembly of Abkhazia passed a resolution, calling upon Russia, international organisations and the rest of the international community to recognise Abkhaz independence on the basis that Abkhazia possesses all the properties of an independent state.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Georgia accuses the Abkhaz secessionists of having conducted a deliberate campaign of ethnic cleansing of up to 250,000 Georgians, a claim supported by the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE; Budapest, Lisbon and Istanbul declaration).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The UN Security Council has avoided the use of the term "ethnic cleansing" but has affirmed "the unacceptability of the demographic changes resulting from the conflict".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] On 15 May 2008, the United Nations General Assembly adopted a non-binding resolution recognising the right of all refugees (including victims of reported "ethnic cleansing") to return to Abkhazia and to retain or regain their property rights there.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] On 3 July 2008, the OSCE Parliamentary Assembly passed a resolution at its annual session in Astana, expressing concern over Russia's recent moves in breakaway Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] On 9 July 2012, the OSCE Parliamentary Assembly passed a resolution at its annual session in Monaco, underlining Georgia's territorial integrity and referring to breakaway Abkhazia and South Ossetia as "occupied territories".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In late October 2008, President Saakashvili signed into law legislation on the occupied territories passed by the Georgian Parliament.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The law covers the breakaway regions of Abkhazia and Tskhinvali (territories of the former South Ossetian Autonomous Oblast).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The law spells out restrictions on free movement and economic activity in the territories.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In particular, according to the law, foreign citizens should enter the two breakaway regions only through Georgia proper.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Entry into Abkhazia should be carried out from the Zugdidi Municipality, and into South Ossetia from the Gori Municipality.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The major road leading to South Ossetia from the rest of Georgia passes through the Gori District.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The legislation, however, also lists "special" cases in which entry into the breakaway regions will not be regarded as illegal.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] It also bans air, sea, and railway communications and international transit via the regions, mineral exploration, and money transfers.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The provision covering economic activities is retroactive, going back to 1990.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The law says that the Russian Federation – the state that has carried out military occupation – is fully responsible for the violation of human rights in Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Russian Federation, according to the document, is also responsible for compensation of material and moral damage inflicted on Georgian citizens, stateless persons, and foreign citizens, who are in Georgia and enter the occupied territories with appropriate permits.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The law also says that de facto state agencies and officials operating in the occupied territories are regarded by Georgia as illegal.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The law will remain in force until "the full restoration of Georgian jurisdiction" over the breakaway regions is realised.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] According to a 2006 report, Georgia considers all residents of Abkhazia its citizens, while they see themselves as Abkhaz citizens.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In the summer of 2011, the Parliament of Georgia adopted a package of legislative amendments providing for the issuance of neutral identification and travel documents to residents of Abkhazia and the former South Ossetian autonomous province of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The document allows travelling abroad as well as enjoying the social benefits existing in Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The new neutral identification and travel documents were called "neutral passports".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The status-neutral passports do not carry the state symbols of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia's foreign minister, Viacheslav Chirikba, criticised the status-neutral passports and called their introduction "unacceptable".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Some Abkhazian residents with Russian passports were being denied Schengen visas.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] As of May 2013, neutral documents have been recognised by Japan, the Czech Republic, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovakia, the United States, Bulgaria, Poland, Israel, Estonia, and Romania.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] During the Georgian–Abkhaz conflict, the Russian authorities and military supplied logistical and military aid to the separatist side.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Today, Russia still maintains a strong political and military influence over separatist rule in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia has also issued passports to the citizens of Abkhazia since 2000 (as Abkhazian passports cannot be used for international travel) and subsequently paid them retirement pensions and other monetary benefits.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] More than 80% of the Abkhazian population had received Russian passports by 2006.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] As Russian citizens living abroad, Abkhazians do not pay Russian taxes or serve in the Russian Army.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] About 53,000 Abkhazian passports have been issued as of May 2007.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Moscow, at certain times, hinted that it might recognise Abkhazia and South Ossetia when Western countries recognised the independence of Kosovo, suggesting that they had created a precedent.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Later in April 2008, Russia accused Georgia of trying to exploit NATO support in order to control Abkhazia by force and announced it would increase its military presence in the region, pledging to retaliate militarily against Georgia's efforts.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Georgian Prime Minister Lado Gurgenidze said Georgia will treat any additional troops in Abkhazia as "aggressors".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In response to the Russo-Georgian War, the Federal Assembly of Russia called an extraordinary session on 25 August 2008 to discuss the recognition of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Following a unanimous resolution passed by both houses of the parliament calling on the Russian president to recognise the independence of the breakaway republics, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev officially recognised both on 26 August 2008.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russian recognition was condemned by NATO member states, OSCE, and European Council members due to "violation of territorial integrity and international law".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon stated that sovereign states have to decide for themselves whether they want to recognise the independence of disputed regions.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia has begun work on the establishment of a naval base in Ochamchire by dredging the coast to allow the passage of its larger naval vessels.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] As a response to the Georgian sea blockade of Abkhazia, in which the Georgian coast guard had been detaining ships heading to and from Abkhazia, Russia warned Georgia against ship seizures and said that a unit of Russian guard boats would provide security for ships bound for Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The extent of Russian influence in Abkhazia has caused some locals to say that Abkhazia is under full Russian control, but they still prefer Russian influence over Georgian.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The UN's position has been that there will be no forcible change of international borders.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Any settlement must be freely negotiated and based on autonomy for Abkhazia, legitimised by referendum under international observation once the multi-ethnic population has returned.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The OSCE has increasingly engaged in dialogue with officials and civil society representatives in Abkhazia, especially from non-governmental organisations (NGOs) and the media, regarding human standards in the region, and is considering a presence in Gali.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The OSCE expressed concern and condemnation over the ethnic cleansing of Georgians in Abkhazia during the 1994 Budapest Summit decision and later at the Lisbon Summit Declaration in 1996.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The US rejects the unilateral secession of Abkhazia and urges its integration into Georgia as an autonomous unit.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 1998, the US announced its readiness to allocate up to $15 million for the rehabilitation of infrastructure in the Gali region if substantial progress is made in the peace process.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] USAID has already funded some humanitarian initiatives for Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] On 5 October 2006, Javier Solana, the High Representative for the Common Foreign and Security Policy of the European Union, ruled out the possibility of replacing the Russian peacekeepers with the EU force.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] On 13 October 2006, the UN Security Council unanimously adopted a resolution, based on a Group of Friends of the Secretary-General draft, extending the UNOMIG mission until 15 April 2007.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Acknowledging that the "new and tense situation" resulted, at least in part, from the Georgian special forces' operation in the upper Kodori Valley, the resolution urged the country to ensure that no troops unauthorised by the Moscow ceasefire agreement were present in that area.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] It urged the leadership of the Abkhaz side to address seriously the need for a dignified, secure return of refugees and internally displaced persons and to reassure the local population in the Gali district that their residency rights and identity would be respected.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Calling on both parties to follow up on dialogue initiatives, it further urged them to comply fully with all previous agreements regarding non-violence and confidence-building, in particular those concerning the separation of forces.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Regarding the disputed role of the peacekeepers from the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), the Council stressed the importance of close, effective cooperation between UNOMIG and that force and looked to all sides to continue to extend the necessary cooperation to them.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The HALO Trust, an international non-profit organisation that specialises in the removal of the debris of war, has been active in Abkhazia since 1999 and has completed the removal of landmines in Sukhumi and Gali districts.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] It declared Abkhazia "mine-free" in 2011.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] France-based international NGO Première-Urgence has been implementing a food security programme to support the vulnerable populations affected by the frozen conflict for almost 10 years.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia does not allow the European Union Monitoring Mission in Georgia (EUMM) to enter Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has been recognised as an independent state by only five states: Russia, Venezuela, Nicaragua, Nauru, and Syria.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Georgia and other countries consider Abkhazia as Georgia's sovereign territory.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia was the first country to officially recognise Abkhazia, which it did after the 2008 Russo-Georgian War.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] After the Russian recognition, Nicaragua, Venezuela, Nauru, Vanuatu, and Tuvalu soon followed suit and recognised Abkhazia and South Ossetia as independent states.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] However, in 2013 and 2014, Vanuatu and Tuvalu scrapped their recognition.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia invested a significant amount of money in a diplomatic strategy to promote the recognition of Abkhazia and South Ossetia and display its soft power.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] However, Russia appeared to have stopped investing in the recognition project after 2014.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] One possible reason could be the worsening of Russia's financial situation following the start of the Russo-Ukrainian war in 2014 and the subsequent imposition of international sanctions on Russia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Consequently, Abkhazia launched its own campaign to strengthen its diplomatic relations with foreign countries and present itself as an independent actor.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] As a part of these efforts, Abkhaz officials paid official visits to numerous countries, including China, Italy, Turkey, and Israel.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Additionally, they held high-level meetings with political representatives from South Africa, Jordan, and El Salvador, and sent diplomatic notes to different countries, including Egypt, France, Guatemala, and Sri Lanka.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] This campaign reached its peak in 2017, but subsequently decreased and largely halted with the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] It was largely unsuccessful and ended in failure as Syria remains the only country that has recognised Abkhazia and South Ossetia since 2009.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] One of the early proposals was voiced before the war, in March 1989, when the Abkhaz ethno-nationalist organisation Aidgylara issued the Lykhny Appeal, calling for Abkhazia to become part of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] This is thought to be a starting point for the Abkhazia conflict between the separatists and local Georgian population in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] After the war, on 18 November 1993, a month after its ending and ethnic cleansing of Georgians in Abkhazia, the leader of Abkhazia Vladislav Ardzinba proposed to hold a referendum to join the Russian Federation.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 2001, a similar desire was voiced by Abkhazia's Prime Minister Anri Jergenia, who said that Abkhazia was preparing to join Russia and that it was going to hold a referendum on that issue.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In October 2022, in an interview to the Russian TV, President of Abkhazia Aslan Bzhania declared Abkhazia's readiness to host a Russian navy and join the Russia-Belarus Union State.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] However, the proposal has been criticised as impractical since Belarus does not recognise Abkhazia as a sovereign state and considers it to be part of Georgia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In August 2023, Deputy Chair of Russian Security Council Dmitry Medvedev also voiced support for these proposals, accusing Georgia of "escalating tensions" by its potential membership to the NATO, and saying that there were "good reasons" for Abkhazia and South Ossetia to join Russia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Medvedev also mocked Georgia's desire to restore its territorial integrity, saying that "Georgia can only be united as part of Russia".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Georgia criticised the proposals for Abkhazia's entry into the Russian Federation and Union State.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 2014, Georgia's Foreign Ministry issued a statement, calling the Russia-Abkhazia treaty on integration a *de facto* annexation.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The economy of Abkhazia is integrated with Russia as outlined in a bilateral agreement published in November 2014.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The country uses the Russian ruble as its currency, and the two countries share a common economic and customs union.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has experienced a modest economic upswing since the 2008 South Ossetia war and Russia's subsequent recognition of Abkhazia's independence.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] About half of Abkhazia's state budget is financed with aid money from Russia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Tourism is a key industry and, according to Abkhazia's authorities, almost a million tourists (mainly from Russia) came to Abkhazia in 2007.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia exports wine and fruits, especially tangerines and hazelnuts.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Electricity is largely supplied by the Inguri hydroelectric power station located on the Inguri River between Abkhazia and Georgia (proper) and operated jointly by both parties.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In the first half of 2012, the principal trading partners of Abkhazia were Russia (64%) and Turkey (18%).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia also called on other CIS members to undertake similar steps, but met with protests from Tbilisi and lack of support from the other CIS countries.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Despite the controversial status of the territory and its damaged infrastructure, tourism in Abkhazia grew following the Russian recognition of Abkhazian independence in 2008 due to the arrival of Russian tourists.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 2009 the number of Russian tourists in Abkhazia increased by 20% and the total number of Russian tourists reached 1 million.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] After the tourist boom many Russian businesses began to invest money in Abkhazian tourist infrastructure.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] With the main highway of the country being rebuilt in 2014 many damaged hotels in Gagra are either being restored or demolished.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 2014, 1.16 million Russian tourists visited Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] According to the last census in 2011 Abkhazia had 240,705 inhabitants.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Department of Statistics of Georgia estimated Abkhazia's population to be approximately 179,000 in 2003, and 178,000 in 2005 (the last year when such estimates were published in Georgia).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] *Encyclopædia Britannica* estimates the population in 2007 at 180,000 and the International Crisis Group estimated Abkhazia's total population in 2006 to be between 157,000 and 190,000 (or between 180,000 and 220,000 as estimated by UNDP in 1998).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The ethnic composition of Abkhazia has played a central role in the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The 1992–1993 war with Georgia resulted in the expulsion and flight of over half of the republic's population, which had numbered 525,061 in the 1989 census.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The population of Abkhazia remains ethnically very diverse, even after the 1992–1993 war.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] At present the population of Abkhazia is mainly made up of ethnic Abkhaz (50.7% according to the 2011 census), Russians, Armenians, Georgians (mostly Mingrelians, but also Svans), and Greeks.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Other ethnicities include Ukrainians, Belarusians, Ossetians, Tatars, Turks, Roma and Estonians.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Greeks constituted a significant minority in the area in the early 1920s (50,000), and remained a major ethnic group until 1945, when they were deported to Central Asia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Under the Soviet Union, the Russian, Armenian, and Georgian populations grew faster than the Abkhaz population, due to large-scale enforced migration, especially under the rule of Joseph Stalin and Lavrenty Beria.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] At the time of the 1989 census, Abkhazia's Georgian population numbered 239,872, forming around 45.7% of the population, and the Armenian population was 77,000.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Due to ethnic cleansing and displacement due to people fleeing the 1992–1993 war, the Georgian population, and to a lesser extent the Russian and Armenian populations, has greatly declined.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 2003 Armenians formed the second-largest minority group in Abkhazia (closely matching the Georgians), numbering 44,869.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] By the time of the 2011 census, Georgians formed the second-largest minority group with a population of 46,455.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Despite the official numbers, unofficial sources estimate that the Abkhaz and Armenian communities are roughly equal in number.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In the wake of the Syrian civil war, Abkhazia granted refugee status to a few hundred Syrians with Abkhaz, Abazin and Circassian ancestry.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Facing a growing Armenian community, this move has been linked with the wish of the ruling Abkhaz —who have often been in the minority on their territory— to tilt the demographic balance in favour of the titular nation.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Thousands of Abkhaz, known as *muhajirun*, were exiled to the Ottoman Empire in the mid-19th century after resisting the Russian conquest of the Caucasus.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Today, Turkey is home to the world's largest Abkhaz diaspora community.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Size estimates vary – diaspora leaders say 1 million people; Abkhaz estimates range from 150,000 to 500,000.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The languages spoken in Abkhazia are Abkhaz, Russian, the Kartvelian languages Mingrelian and Svan, Armenian, and Greek.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Autonomous Republic passed a law in 2007 defining the Abkhaz language as the only state language of Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] As such, Abkhaz is the required language for legislative and executive council debates (with translation from and to Russian) and at least half of the text of all magazines and newspapers must be in Abkhaz.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Despite the official status of Abkhaz, the dominance of other languages within Abkhazia, especially Russian, is so great that experts called it an "endangered language" in 2004.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] During the Soviet era, language instruction would begin in schools in Abkhaz, only to switch to Russian for the majority of required schooling.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The government of the Republic is attempting to institute Abkhaz-only primary education but there has been limited success due to a lack of facilities and educational materials.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The primary schools in Kartvelian-speaking areas switched from Georgian to Russian in 2016.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] A majority of inhabitants of Abkhazia are Christian (Eastern Orthodox (see also: Abkhazian Orthodox Church) and Armenian Apostolic) while a significant minority are Sunni Muslim.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhaz Native Religion has undergone a strong revival in recent decades.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] There is a very small number of adherents of Judaism, Jehovah's Witnesses and new religious movements.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Jehovah's Witnesses organisation has officially been banned since 1995, though the decree is not currently enforced.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] According to the constitution of Abkhazia, the adherents of all religions have equal rights before the law.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] According to a survey held in 2003, 60% of respondents identified themselves as Christian, 16% as Muslim, 8% as atheist or irreligious, 8% as adhering to the traditional Abkhazian religion or as Pagan, 2% as follower of other religions and 6% as undecided.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] After the break-up of the Soviet Union, many Abkhazians kept their Soviet passports, even after a decade, and used them to eventually apply for Russian citizenship.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Before 2002, Russian law allowed residents of former Soviet Union to apply for citizenship if they had not become citizens of their newly independent states.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The new citizenship law of Russia adopted on 31 May 2002 introduced a simplified procedure of citizenship acquisition for former citizens of the Soviet Union regardless of their place of residence.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In Abkhazia and South Ossetia, the application process was simplified even further, and people could apply even without leaving their homes.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russian non-governmental organisations with close ties to Russian officialdom simply took their papers to a nearby Russian city for processing.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazians began mass acquisition of Russian passports in 2002.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] It is reported that the public organisation the Congress of Russian Communities of Abkhazia started collecting Abkhazians' Soviet-era travel documents.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] It then sent them to a consular department specially set up by Russian Foreign Ministry officials in the city of Sochi.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] After they were checked, Abkhazian applicants were granted Russian citizenship.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] By 25 June 2002, an estimated 150,000 people in Abkhazia had acquired the new passports, joining 50,000 who already possessed Russian citizenship.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Sukhum authorities, although officially not involved in the registration for Russian nationality process, openly encouraged it.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Government officials said privately that President Putin's administration agreed with the passport acquisition during Abkhazia's prime minister Djergenia's visit to Moscow in May 2002.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] When the *"passportisation"* policy was launched in 2002, even Russia recognised Abkhazia as part of Georgia at that time.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Russia's extraterritorial naturalisation practice in South Ossetia and Abkhazia constituted an intervention contrary to international law and it violated Georgia's territorial sovereignty.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The passportisation caused outrage in Tbilisi, worsening its already shaky relations with Russia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Georgian Foreign Ministry issued a statement insisting that Abkhazians were citizens of Georgia and calling the passport allocation an "unprecedented illegal campaign".
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] President Eduard Shevardnadze said that he would be asking his Russian counterpart, Vladimir Putin, for an explanation.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The speaker of parliament Nino Burjanadze said that she would raise the matter at the forthcoming OSCE parliamentary assembly.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] 1 February 2011 was the last day in the post-Soviet era when a passport of USSR was valid for crossing the Russian-Abkhaz border.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] According to the staff of Abkhazia's passport and visa service, there were about two to three thousand mostly elderly people left with Soviet passports who had no chance of acquiring new documents.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] These people were not able to get Russian citizenship.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] But they can first get an internal Abkhaz passport and then a travelling passport to visit Russia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 2005, citing the need to integrate ethnic Georgian residents of eastern districts of Abkhazia, the then leadership of Abkhazia showed signs of a softening stance towards granting of citizenship to the residents of Gali, Ochamchire and Tkvarcheli districts.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] According to the Abkhazian law on citizenship, ethnic Abkhazians, regardless of place of residence, can become Abkhaz citizens.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Those who are not ethnic Abkhazians are eligible for citizenship if they lived in Abkhazia for at least five years prior to the adoption of the act of independence in October 1999.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] This provision aimed at creating a legal hurdle in obtaining Abkhaz passports for those ethnic Georgians who fled Abkhazia as a result of 1992–1993 armed conflict and who then returned to the Gali district.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazian legislation forbids citizens of Abkhazia from holding dual citizenship with any other state apart from Russia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Ethnic Georgians who have returned to the Gali district and want to obtain Abkhaz passports, according to Abkhazian law, should undergo lengthy procedures which also include a requirement to submit documented proof that they renounced their Georgian citizenship.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] So in his official speeches, Bagapsh often added the Gali Georgians to population estimates of the Abkhaz, disregarding the fact that they still thought of themselves as ethnic Georgians rather than Abkhaz.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In early 2013 the process of passportisation of ethnic Georgians came under the scrutiny of Abkhaz opposition groups who turned this issue into one of the central topics of the breakaway region's internal politics, and issuing of passports was suspended in May.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Pressures have been placed upon teachers in areas of Abkhazia which retain large Georgian populations to abandon the use of the Georgian language in education and adopt Russian textbooks.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] According to the Abkhaz officials, more than 26,000 passports were distributed in Gali, Tkvarcheli and Ochamchire districts, including about 23,000 of which were given out since Russian recognition of Abkhazia's independence in August 2008.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] These political debates have caused concerns in the ethnic Georgian population of Abkhazia, who reside mainly in Gali district, that they would be stripped of Abkhazian citizenship and thus forced to leave Abkhazia again.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In October 2013 Alexander Ankvab signed a document ordering the firing of Stanislav Lakoba.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The document did not state any reason for the decision but Lakoba saw it as related to his political position on granting citizenship to Georgians living in Gali.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Lakoba claimed that, according to data from the Abkhaz Security Council, 129 local people in Gali fought against Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Local political parties and the coordination council of civil organisations expressed concern about Lakoba's dismissal.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] They claimed that, by dismissing him, the president "made an illegal process legal" – giving Abkhazian passports to Georgian citizens.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Until the 19th century, young people from Abkhazia usually received their education mainly at religious schools (Muslims at madrasas and Christians at seminaries), although a small number of children from wealthy families had opportunity to travel to foreign countries for education.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The first modern educational institutions (both schools and colleges) in Abkhazia were established in the late 19th-early 20th centuries and rapidly grew until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] By the middle of the 20th century, Sukhumi had become a home for large educational institutions (both higher education institutions and technical vocational education and training (TVET) colleges) and largest students' community in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] According to the official statistical data, Abkhazia has 12 TVET colleges (as of 2019, est.) providing education and vocational training to youth mostly in the capital city, though there are several colleges in all major district centres.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Independent international assessments suggest that these colleges train in about 20 different specialties attracting between 1000 and 1300 young people annually (aged between 16 and 29) (as of 2019, est.).
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The apsuara, the Abkhaz code of honour, is very stringent regarding hospitality.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] One of its principles is to respect guests even if they have committed crimes against the host.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The written Abkhaz literature appeared relatively recently, in the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] However, Abkhaz share the Nart sagas, a series of tales about mythical heroes, with other Caucasian peoples.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhaz alphabet was created in the 19th century.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The first newspaper in Abkhaz, called *Abkhazia* and edited by Dmitry Gulia, appeared in 1917.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Arguably the most famous Abkhaz writers are Fazil Iskander, who wrote mostly in Russian, and Bagrat Shinkuba, a poet and writer.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Football remains the most popular sport in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Other popular sports include basketball, boxing and wrestling.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] The National Basketball Team of Abkhazia played its first game with the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Basketball team on 27 May 2015, which Abkhaz team won by 76–59.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhaz basketball team "Apsny" also plays in the Russian Basketball League's Third-Tier in Krasnodar Krai.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has had its own amateur football league called the Abkhazian Premier League, but it has no international football union membership.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In total, there are nineteen Abkhazian Football Clubs across the two leagues.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] In 2016 it hosted and won the ConIFA World Football Cup.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Since the early 2000s, tennis has become increasingly popular among school age children in Abkhazia.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] Several tennis players from Sukhumi participated as the national competitions in Russia and played at major international competitions under the Russian flag.
[src:abkhazia/abkhazia-p02] For example, tennis player Alen Avidzba participated at the Davis Cup in 2016 and Amina Anshba won a silver medal at an international tournament in Turkey in 2017.
